<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Chief Arrives in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- World Bank President James
Wolfensohn arrived here on Sunday, starting his official visit to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time that the World Bank chief pays a visit
to the country after the Kosovo crisis ended, and the second time
he comes to the country since he became the bank's president in
1995, according to Ana Gjokutaj, a press liaison officer working
with the bank's Tirana Office.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of Wolfensohn's visit is to see in person the
actual situation in the country after the Kosovo crisis and
discuss the bank's cooperation plans in future with the Albanian
government.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn was met by Albanian Prime Minister Pandeli Majko at
the Rinas airport when he arrived late afternoon on the day. Local
media said that the two sides held talks on the issues of common
concern, including some financing projects by the bank.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn will visit Macedonia and Kosovo after he closes his
visit to Albania on Monday, Gjokutaj added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
