<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Calls for Joint Efforts to Revive Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has
called for intensified efforts by parties concerned to bring the
deadlocked Middle East peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made in a message conveyed to Jordanian King
Abdullah Bin Hussein by Egyptian Ambassador to Jordan Hani Riyad
during his meeting with the Jordanian ruler at the Royal Court
here.
</P>
<P>
In the message, Mubarak briefed Abdullah on the outcome of his
recent visit to the United States and France aimed at breaking the
deadlock in the Mideast peace process, Jordan's official news
agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
On his visit to Washington, Mubarak said that there was an
American understanding of the importance of resuming peace talks
between Israel and its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian leader said that the prevailing conditions in the
region provided an opportunity to revive the peace process, and
joint support must be provided to the resumption of peace talks
between Israel, the Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was apparently referring to the atmosphere arose from
the swear-in of Israel's new Prime Minister Ehud Barak, who had
pledged, during a brief visit to Amman on Wednesday, to comply
with all agreements his country had signed with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Barak's speech marked a far cry from his predecessor Benjamin
Netanyahu, whose hard-line policies during his three years in
office had been blamed by Arab countries for the stalemate of
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
