<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Free Longest-Held Palestinian Detainee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Israel's High Court agreed
Sunday to release the longest-held Palestinian detainee who has
been imprisoned for almost six years without trial.
</P>
<P>
The court approved an agreement made between Israeli military
authorities and West Bank resident Osama Barham, who was arrested
in 1993 for his membership in the militant Islamic Jihad group,
over the terms of his release, according to a court spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Barham, who said he had no idea what the charges against him
were, pledged in the agreement that he will refrain from violence
against Israel and register with police every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Israeli television reports said more than 60 Palestinians and
about 20 Lebanese civilians are being held by Israel without
charge or trial, with the length of their detentions ranging from
several months to several years.
</P>
<P>
Under the Israeli "administrative detention" law, prisoners can
be held without trial for easily renewable six-month
periods. Israel argued that such administrative detention is
needed in cases where Israel's security is threatened by
militants.
</P>
<P>
It's hard to tell if the release is an individual case or a
good-will gesture by the new Israeli government of Prime Minister
Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Winning the election in May, Barak has pledged to abide by the
Wye interim agreement with the Palestinians, signed and then
frozen by his predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu last year. The
accord calls for the release of 750 Palestinian political
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu ordered the release of 250 prisoners last November
in the first of the three phases of the agreement, but most of
them were common criminals. The dispute sparked weeks of bloody
conflict between Israeli soldiers and the Palestinians in the
West Bank and Gaza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
