<HEADLINE> URGENT: Chinese, U.S. Presidents Confer over Phone (More Added) (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
reiterated China's solemn stand on the Taiwan issue in a telephone
conversation with U.S. President Bill Clinton tonight.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton reiterated the U.S. government's "strong
commitment" to adhering to its "one China" policy on the Taiwan
Issue.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president had the telephone conversation tonight
with President Clinton at the latter's request.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that "the purpose of calling is to reiterate our
strong commitment to the 'one China' policy."
</P>
<P>
"I want to assure you that policy will not change, you should
have full confidence in the statements I have made to you in our
previous meetings," Clinton told Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that they have talked about the Taiwan issue several
times, and in 1998 when President Clinton visited China, they had
a frank and in-depth exchange of views on that issue.
</P>
<P>
At that time, Jiang said, he repeatedly stressed that the
Taiwan issue involves China's sovereignty and territorial
integrity, its cause of peaceful reunification and the national
sentiment of the entire Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The realization of the reunification of the motherland is the
strong determination of the Chinese government, and is also the
common aspiration of the entire Chinese people, including Taiwan
compatriots and overseas compatriots as well, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that recently, Lee Teng-hui flagrantly described
the cross-strait relations as "state-to-state" relations, which is
a very dangerous step he has taken toward splitting the country,
and a severe provocation to the "one China" principle recognized
by the international community.
</P>
<P>
This further exposed Lee's nature to split China's territory
and sovereignty, and his attempt to separate Taiwan from China,
Jiang said, reaffirming that there is only one China in the world,
and Taiwan is part of Chinese territory, and China's territory and
sovereignty absolutely brooks no separation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that our basic principle for solving the Taiwan
issue remains "peaceful reunification and one country, two systems
". We have been actively promoting personnel and economic
exchanges between the two sides of the Taiwan Straits, and have
also been working for direct links in mail, shipping and trade,
and promoting the cross-strait political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
However, Jiang stressed, we are not committed to abandoning the
use of force on the issue of Taiwan. The reason is very clear,
that is, there are certain forces in both Taiwan island and the
world that attempt to separate Taiwan from the motherland.
</P>
<P>
We will never sit idle if some people engage in "Taiwan's
independence" and foreign forces interfere in China's
reunification cause, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang pointed out that the reaction of the Chinese government
and people to Lee Teng-hui's splittist remarks has demonstrated
the strong determination of the Chinese government and people to
oppose splitting motherland, safeguard state sovereignty and
territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
We have warned the Taiwan authorities to rein in at the edge of
precipice and stop various actions of splittism to avoid serious
consequences to the relations and situations across the Taiwan
Straits, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang emphasized that the anti-China force in the United States
remains rampant and some people there still favor the splittist
attempt on "Taiwan independence" and spare no effort to support
the "independence force" on the Taiwan island.
</P>
<P>
History proves that the handling of the Taiwan issue will have
a direct impact on the process of Sino-U.S. relations, Jiang said,
hoping that the U.S. will earnestly abide by the three Sino-U.S.
joint communiques and by the commitment not to supporting "Taiwan
independence," "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan," and Taiwan
's access into any international organizations that only admit
sovereign state, which President Clinton publicly reiterated
during his China visit last year and was recently reaffirmed by
the White House.
</P>
<P>
This is of vital importance to maintaining the stability of the
situation across the Taiwan Straits and to restoring and improving
Sino-U.S. relations, Jiang stressed.
</P>
<P>
On the Sino-U.S. relations, Clinton said that the U.S.-China
relations are very important and can not be undermined, adding
that he will work hard to improve the relations between the two
countries as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that the Chinese government has always pay great
attention to developing the Sino-U.S. relations, and hoped that
the U.S. side will properly handle the problems now facing the
bilateral relations from strategic heights and long-term
perspectives.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
