<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most UK Firms Want Delayed Euro Entry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The Confederation of British
Industry (CBI) has backed joining the euro but do not favor early
entry, British papers said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A poll of 5,000 CBI members conducted by research group Mori
will be published on Tuesday and will reveal that companies in
favor of the single currency outnumber those against it by three
to one, according to the Observer.
</P>
<P>
Most members are believed to have voted for membership between
2002 and 2005. The results come against the background of the euro
dropping to a record low of 1.01 U.S. dollars last week.
</P>
<P>
Earlier evidence has showed that the CBI supports British
membership of the euro in principle but some companies have been
split on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Last week an ICM poll indicated that if a referendum were held
now, 62 percent of respondents would vote against, and last month
the Institute of Directors found more than half its members
against joining. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
