<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 14 Iraqi Civilians Killed in U.S., British Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Fourteen Iraqi civilians were
killed and 17 others injured on Sunday in U.S. and British
warplanes bombardment of some civilian buildings in southern Iraq,
an Iraqi military spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 11:30 (0730 GMT) and 17:40
(1340 GMT), a total of 16 formations of enemy warplanes coming
from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases violated southern Iraqi airspace
and bombed some civilian buildings in this area.
</P>
<P>
This is the heaviest civilian casualties caused by U.S. and
British air raids this year in their regular attacks on Iraqi
civilian and military targets in the no-fly zones in the north
and south of the country.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the U.S. and Britain launched four-night
airstrikes against Iraq, leading to the deaths of hundreds of
Iraqi civilians and soldiers and the injuries in thousands.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that nine formations of U.S. and British
warplanes coming from Turkey also violated northern Iraqi
airspace at 11:00 (0700 GMT) Sunday and attacked some civilian
facilities in the area.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back at the invading enemy
planes and forced them to flee to their bases, he added.
</P>
<P>
Since last December, the U.S. and British warplanes have made
more than 10,200 sorties over the northern and southern no-fly
zones in Iraq, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in Iraq
in the wake of the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south from any possible attacks by the government troops.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's U.S.-British bombardment, Iraq has
declared that it does not recognize the restricted zones and vows
to fire at any western planes violating its airspace.
</P>
<P>
U.S. and British warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi
civilian and military targets ever since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denktash Says He May Attend Cyprus Talks If His </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash said on Sunday that he may attend talks on the Cyprus
issue if the "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus" is recognized
as a state.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Turkey's private BRT
television, Denktash stressed that "Let's talk about an agreement
between the two states on Cyprus from now on, not discuss a
solution. The name of this is confederation."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his readiness "to sign good neighborhood and
cooperation agreement between the states on the island of Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, Denktash declared the breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus," which is now recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has been trying for decades to reunite the
island through a bi-communal federation formula, but the talks
between the two sides have made no substantive progress so far.
</P>
<P>
Denktash added that "the Greek Cypriot side escapes from
discussing the confederation and federation, tries to destroy
Turkey's guarantorship and does not accept exchange of
properties."
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots will never make concessions on their
sovereignty, said Denktash, adding that "there can't be a quarter
or half sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
In a unanimously approved resolution on June 29, the
U.N. Security Council urged U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
invite the Turkish and Greek Cypriot sides to resume talks.
</P>
<P>
Under the resolution, the talks should start with no
preconditions, all aspects of the conflict should be on the table
and the negotiations last until a settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution followed a similar appeal by the Group of
Eight (G-8), which groups the U.S., Canada, Britain, France,
Italy, Germany, Japan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the G-8 had urged Annan "to invite the leaders
of the two parties on Cyprus to negotiations in the fall of
1999." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
