<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak's Aides Defend His Timetable for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Senior aides to Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak on Sunday defended his newly-set 15-month
timetable for final peace agreements on all tracks, saying it is
a target date rather than a firm commitment.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media revealed that during their talks, Barak and
U.S. President Bill Clinton believe peace breakthroughs can be
made both with Syria and the Palestinians before the U.S. elections
in November 2000. Barak is on a week-long visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
Critics in Israel said that setting such a target would encourage
Arab parties to raise their demand in hopes that Israel would
make last-minute concessions in order to meet the deadline.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy told a weekly cabinet meeting that
the aim of the timetable is to show Israel's eagerness to push
forward the peace process on all tracks as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
Barak's chief-of-staff Danny Yatom, accompanying Barak on his
first U.S. visit, said in a telephone interview with Israel Radio
that the 15-month period is not a time limit.
</P>
<P>
"This is a new window of opportunity...This is our assessment
shared by the Americans that in the timetable of about 15 months,
we will be able to know if we are going to reach breakthrough or
not," he said.
</P>
<P>
After returning from his visit, which was aimed at
coordinating Israeli and U.S. efforts to revive the peace talks,
Barak will outline his peace plans through consultation with
Egypt, Jordan and the Palestinians, Yatom said.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials made no comment on Barak's timetable,
but urged him to implement the Wye interim agreement signed by
his predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu last October.
</P>
<P>
Barak has called for the combination of the Wye agreement with
the final-status talks with the Palestinians, but the
Palestinians have demanded the full implementation of the interim
deal which calls for Israel to withdraw from an additional 13
percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu froze the Wye agreement last December after carrying
out the first of its three stages. The final status talks, in
which the thorny issues like the fate of Jerusalem and
Palestinian refugees will be dealt with, have yet to start.
</P>
<P>
Barak said over the weekend that he had called Palestinian
National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat to brief him on his
visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
The two are said to have agreed to meet immediately after
Barak's return for their second summit meeting since the new
Israeli prime minister took office early this month.
</P>
<P>
Levy described as "positive" Syrian media reports which said a
peace agreement will be reached in a period of less than 15
months, but he stressed that it is time for Damascus to take
concrete actions.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks were frozen in the last three years
since they broke off in early 1996, with the two sides disputing
over how the talks should be restarted.
</P>
<P>
Damascus demanded the talks resume from where they left off, a
verbal promise from the former Labor government to return to
Syria the Golan Heights, a strategic plateau seized by Israel in
the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
But the hard-line government of Netanyahu, which opposed any
territorial concession over Golan, denied the existence of such a
promise.
</P>
<P>
Since defeating Netanyahu in the May election, Barak has
exchanged compliments with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad and
expressed their readiness to resume the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: Chinese, U.S. Presidents Confer over Phone (More Added) (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
reiterated China's solemn stand on the Taiwan issue in a telephone
conversation with U.S. Presdient Bill Clinton tonight.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton reiterated the U.S. government's "strong
commitment" to adhering to its "one China" policy on the Taiwan
Issue.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president had the telephone conversation tonight
with President Clinton at the latter's request.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that "the purpose of calling is to reiterate our
strong commitment to the 'one China' policy."
</P>
<P>
"I want to assure you that policy will not change, you should
have full confidence in the statements I have made to you in our
previous meetings," Clinton told Jiang.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that they have talked about the Taiwan issue several
times, and in 1998 when President Clinton visited China, they had
a frank and in-depth exchange of views on that issue.
</P>
<P>
At that time, Jiang said, he repeatedly stressed that the
Taiwan issue involves China's sovereignty and territorial
integrity, its cause of peaceful reunification and the national
sentiment of the entire Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The realization of the reunification of the motherland is the
strong determination of the Chinese government, and is also the
common aspiration of the entire Chinese people, including Taiwan
compatriots and overseas compatriots as well, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that recently, Lee Teng-hui flagrantly described
the cross-strait relations as "state-to-state" relations, which is
a very dangerous step he has taken toward splitting the country,
and a severe provocation to the "one China" principle recognized
by the international community.
</P>
<P>
This further exposed Lee's nature to split China's territory
and sovereignty, and his attempt to separate Taiwan from China,
Jiang said, reaffirming that there is only one China in the world,
and Taiwan is part of Chinese territory, and China's territory and
sovereignty absolutely brooks no separation.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that our basic principle for solving the Taiwan
issue remains "peaceful reunification and one country, two systems
". We have been actively promoting personnel and economic
exchanges between the two sides of the Taiwan Straits, and have
also been working for direct links in mail, shipping and trade,
and promoting the cross-strait political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
However, Jiang stressed, we are not committed to abandoning the
use of force on the issue of Taiwan. The reason is very clear,
that is, there are certain forces in both Taiwan island and the
world that attempt to separate Taiwan from the motherland.
</P>
<P>
We will never sit idle if some people engage in "Taiwan's
independence" and foreign forces interfere in China's
reunification cause, Jiang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Announces Purchase of 50 F-16 Fight Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Ministry on
Sunday officially announced the purchase of 50 F-16 fighter jets
from Lockheed Martin in a deal worth 2.5 billion U.S. dollars,
the largest ever defense contract signed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister and Defense Minister Ehud Barak decided that
Israel will buy the F-16 plane as the air force's new fighter,"
the ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came two days after Israeli government
officials accompanying Barak on a visit to the U.S. told Lockheed
that they will buy 50 of their fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
Words of the deal came following Barak's meeting with
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen Friday. Barak told both
President Bill Clinton and Cohen that he had decided to accept
the recommendation of the Israeli army and to go ahead with the
purchase.
</P>
<P>
The contract, expected to be signed by August 20, also gives
Israel the option to buy up to 60 additional fighters within two
years.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Israeli defense firms will get 900 million
U.S. dollars in new contracts as part of the deal, details of
which were not revealed.
</P>
<P>
The deal ended months of heated competition between Lockheed,
which produces the cheaper and more agile single-engined F-16,
and Boeing, which manufactures the heavier, multi-role
twin-engined F-15, since Washington agreed last September to sell
Israel 2.5 billion U.S. dollars worth of fighter jets.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Defense Ministry had considered to split the
contract between the two companies, but former defense minister
Moshe Arens decided last month to buy F-16 fighters from
Lockheed. He then left the final decision to the new prime
minister as he requested.
</P>
<P>
Lockheed, which delivered the first of Israel's 260 F-16 jets
in the early 1980s, lost a bid to Boeing in 1994, because Israel
needed the long-rang F-15I fighters to counter potential
belligerence from Iraq and Iran.
</P>
<P>
It came into the latest deal with a conformal fuel tanks made
by Israel Aircraft Industries which increased its plane's range
to nearly match that of the F-15I fighters.
</P>
<P>
Barak's visit to Washington, the first since he took office
early this month, was designed to enhance Israeli-U.S. strategic
and military ties as well as to coordinate efforts on the Middle
East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-18 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani PM in Saudi Arabia for Talks on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif arrived in the western Saudi city of Jeddah on
Sunday for talks with Saudi officials on the development of
the Kashmir crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwait News Agency quoted Pakistani diplomatic sources in
Saudi Arabia as saying that Sharif's two-day official visit is
aimed at briefing the Saudi leadership on the latest developments
of the crisis with India over disputed Kashmir and Pakistan's
stance on efforts to solve the issue.
</P>
<P>
The sources reaffirmed Pakistan's keenness to settle the
crisis with India through negotiations and on the basis of
concerned agreements signed by both countries, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports reaching here said that India has signaled
on Saturday the end of the 53-day war with Pakistan in the
Kashimr region. New Delhi announced that all the infiltrators
it claimed supported by Pakistan's armed forces had withdrawn
from the Indian-controled Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Pakistani sources stressed that Sharif's visit
to the Gulf kingdom also reflects deep-rooted relations between
the two nations, adding that Islamabad considers Riyadh as a
heavyweight in the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
Sharif will hold talks later in the day with Saudi Crown
Prince and Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz on
ways of boosting bilateral ties in the fields of economy,
trade and investment, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
