<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Charles Wang, Chinese American Who Founds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
 World-Class Software Company
</P>
<P>
by Gu Zhenqiu
</P>
<P>
NEW ORLEANS, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The secret of success for Computer
Associates International (CA), the leading software company in the
world, is that make every staff member feel that they can contribute
something to the bright future of the company, and their work is
very valuable, the CA boss, Charles B. Wang, told reporters on
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The CA chief made the remarks at a press conference before the annual
CA meeting, termed as CA World 1999, is scheduled to kick off here on
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Wang, one of the overseas Chinese in the United States, is CA's
chairman and chief executive officer, the world leader in
mission-critical business software.
</P>
<P>
With revenue of 5.3 billion U.S. dollars in fiscal year 1999,
CA employs more than 14,000 people in 100 countries around the
world.
</P>
<P>
Wang founded CA in 1976, launching the company with three
associates, a single product and a simple idea: that technology must
serve business. Today, CA software provides the computing
foundation for hundreds of thousands of businesses all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
The CA boss combines a strategic business perspective with a
hands-on grasp of technology. He has also ensured that CA retains
its enterpreneurial spark by fostering a supportive culture and
flexible corporate structure.
</P>
<P>
"Any software is only as good as the company that stands behind
it," he said, "That's why smart clients always find out as much as
they can about the company, the resources, and the people behind the
software before they invest."
</P>
<P>
CA continues to outpace other software providers while setting
industry standards in enterprise computing. CA's basic strategy --
the development, acquisition and interaction of software -- delivers
a mission-critical multi-platform infrastructure that exploits new
technologies.
</P>
<P>
A technology visionary with a no-nonsense management style, Wang
is actively involved in CA's ongoing research and development
efforts. He meets frequently with clients to exchange programs to
help chief information officers and chief executive officers better
100 best-manage manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
He also established the Smile Train, an unprecedented medical
and technology initiative dedicated to helping children with cleft
lips and palates and other facial deformities.
</P>
<P>
Wang has endowed 25 million U.S. dollars for a high technology
Asian American Center at the State University of New York (SUNY) at
Stony Brook, the largest private gift in the history of the SUNY
system. The center will be dedicated to the advancement of
education, cultural exchanges, businesses and technology.
</P>
<P>
Wang was born in Shanghai, east China, in August 1944 and came
to the United States with his family in 1952. He earned a Bachelor
of Science degree in Maths from Queens College, and began his
computer career at the prestigious Columbia University's Riverside
Research Institute, where he started as a programming trainee. He
later served as vice president of sales for Standard Data
Corporation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
