<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economic Performance in Sub-Sahara Improves: IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Sub-Saharan Africa's economic
performance has shown substantial improvement in recent years,
based largely on improved policies, according to the International
Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
It said, however, sub-Saharan Africa still had a long way to go
to make a real dent in pervasive poverty, begin catching up with
other developing regions and integrate itself fully into the
global economy, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The overall economic situation is fragile, as evidenced by the
slowdown in economic growth and the increase in financial
imbalances in 1998, owing to poor weather, weak commodity prices
and armed conflicts," the lending institution said in its July
Survey.
</P>
<P>
The institution said structural adjustment was essential for
all African countries, requiring perseverance in policy
implementation and reforms that were consistent and sustainable.
</P>
<P>
It underscored the importance of a new partnership with
industrial countries that recognized and acted on Africa's need
for more open trade, more foreign direct investment, greater
transfer of technology and deeper debt relief.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said it would continue to support strong reform
programs with financial and technical assistance as well as
training designed to enhance administrative and technical
capacity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
