<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, July 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash said on Sunday
that he may attend talks on the Cyprus issue if the "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" is recognized as a state.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with Turkey's private BRT
television, Denktash stressed that "Let's talk about an agreement
between the two states on Cyprus from now on, not discuss a
solution. The name of this is confederation."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his readiness "to sign good neighborhood and
cooperation agreement between the states on the island of Cyprus."
(BC-Turkey-Cyprus-Talks)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Defense Ministry on Sunday officially
announced the purchase of 50 F-16 fighter jets from Lockheed
Martin in a deal worth 2.5 billion U.S. dollars, the largest ever
defense contract signed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister and Defense Minister Ehud Barak decided that
Israel will buy the F-16 plane as the air force's new fighter,"
the ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came two days after Israeli government
officials accompanying Barak on a visit to the U.S. told Lockheed
that they will buy 50 of their fighter jets.
(BC-Israel-US-Fighters)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel's High Court agreed Sunday to release the
longest-held Palestinian detainee who has been imprisoned for
almost six years without trial.
</P>
<P>
The court approved an agreement made between Israeli military
authorities and West Bank resident Osama Barham, who was arrested
in 1993 for his membership in the militant Islamic Jihad group,
over the terms of his release, according to a court spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Barham, who said he had no idea what the charges against him
were, pledged in the agreement that he will refrain from violence
against Israel and register with police every two weeks.
(BC-Israel-Prisoner)
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Fourteen Iraqi civilians were killed and 17 others
injured on Sunday in U.S. and British warplanes bombardment of
some civilian buildings in southern Iraq, an Iraqi military
spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 11:30 (0730 GMT) and 17:40
(1340 GMT), a total of 16 formations of enemy warplanes coming
from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases violated southern Iraqi airspace
and bombed some civilian buildings in this area.
</P>
<P>
This is the heaviest civilian casualties caused by U.S. and
British air raids this year in their regular attacks on Iraqi
civilian and military targets in the no-fly zones in the north
and south of the country. (BC-Iraq-US Attack)  
</P>
</TEXT>
