<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Currency to Stabilize: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 18 (Xinhua) -- The central Bank of Tanzania
has assured people that the depreciation of Tanzanian shilling is
a temporary phenomenon and the currency will stabilize.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian shilling depreciated at an alarming rate of some
10 percent in the past three weeks. In private foreign exchange
centers, the mean rate stood at around 810 shillings per U.S.
dollar at the weekend, compared with 734 on June 28, triggering
fears that the currency is unreliable.
</P>
<P>
Daudi Ballali, the central bank governor, said Saturday that
one of the reasons for the depreciation was low exports of both
traditional and non- traditional goods during the past two years
due to adverse weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
A foreign exchange dealer told Xinhua Sunday that the amount of
U.S. dollars released by the central bank to the auction market
has reduced from one million to between 200,000 and 300,000 a day
during the past month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
