<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Nuclear Shipment Heads to Japan After Protests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 19 (Xinhua) - A British nuclear shipment, which
had been prevented by environmental activists from leaving a
harbour in northwest England, finally headed to sea on Monday on
the first leg of its journey to Japan, British Nuclear Fuels Ltd
(BNFL) said.
</P>
<P>
"I can confirm that (the ship named Pacific) Teal is on its
way. It has moved out of the harbour and is out in the open sea,"
a Reuters report quoted a spokesman for BNFL as saying.
</P>
<P>
But the spokesman did not know if a second ship, which was also
forced by protesters to keep in the docks, had left harbour yet.
</P>
<P>
The Pacific Teal was earlier forced to return to its berth at
Barrow because of safety concerns sparked by an overnight protest
by the environmental group Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
The Greenpeace group said it was fearing environmental fallout,
nuclear proliferation and possible hijacking on the high seas.
</P>
<P>
Seven people were arrested during the demonstration. Greenpeace
said earlier Monday it would not make another attempt to stop the
ships leaving the harbour.
</P>
<P>
The Pacific Teal is due to head for a port city in France, en
route to Japan, where the plutonium fuel is to be loaded into
nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace said the two ships' combined cargo could be
converted into 60 bombs.
</P>
<P>
BNFL denied the plutonium was ever at risk and said the
security arrangements fully satisfied a U.S.-Japan nuclear pact,
under which Tokyo needs U.S. consent to ship plutonium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
