<HEADLINE> Flood Threat Increasing in East China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANCHANG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The water levels of major rivers,
lakes, and reservoirs in Jiangxi Province, east China, have all
been above the danger marks since July 1, resulting in four
billion yuan of direct economic losses.
</P>
<P>
Because of continued rainfall on the upper and middle reaches
of the Yangtze River, the water level at the city of Jiujiang in
Jiangxi had risen to 22.21 meters by 8:00 am today, 2.71 meters
above the danger line, and the level monitored at the Hukou
hydrologic station by Poyang Lake climbed to 21.72 metes, 2.72
meters above the danger mark. More than 600 leaks and cave-ins
have been reported by now at some waterlogged levees and dikes.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that water levels at Jiujiang and Hukou County
will reach 22.5 and 22 meters respectively by around July 22.
Local governments have asked for greater efforts to guard against
severe flooding, and about one million people are now keeping a
watch on levees and dikes day and night near the Yangtze River and
Poyang Lake.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
