<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Official Denies Chemical Weapons on Kola Peninsula </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A ranking Russian official on
Monday denied the reported presence of chemical weapons in the
Kola Peninsula in northwestern Russia, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The denial, by Colonel-General Stanislav Petrov, commander of
the radiation, chemical and biological protection service, was in
response to reports in Verdens Gang, a Norwegian newspaper, that
the Russian army has a secrete store of chemical weapons in the
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The Kola Peninsula projects eastward from Scandinavia between
the White Sea and the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
Russia has revealed all its stores of chemical weapons "which
are regularly visited by international inspection teams," Petrov
said.
</P>
<P>
"The Hague-based organization for banning chemical weapons has
not complained about any Russian misbehavior," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said any country, in particular Norway, can demand through
this organization an inspection tour of any area.
</P>
<P>
"However, this costs money and results in political costs if
the complaints prove false," Petrov said, "This is why some find
it easier to make unfounded accusations through the mass media."
</P>
<P>
In 1993, representatives from 160 nations approved the
Chemical Weapons Convention, which banned the production, use,
sale, and storage of all chemical weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
