<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South African Cabinet Okays U.N. Anti-Apartheid Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The South African cabinet has
approved that parliament be requested to accede to the United
Nations International Convention on the Suppression and the
Punishment of the Crime of Apartheid, Justice Minister Penuell
Maduna said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The South African government is committed to the eradication
of all forms of apartheid or racial discrimination and will submit
periodic reports as required by the convention once acceded to by
our parliament, to the U.N. Commission on Human Rights about
legislative, judicial, administrative or other measures adopted to
give effect to the provision of the convention," the Justice
Department said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The convention was adopted and opened for signature,
ratification and accession by the U.N. General Assembly on
November 30, 1973 and came into operation on July 18, 1976.
</P>
<P>
The main purpose of the convention is to declare apartheid as a
crime and to criminalize acts of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
"It is with deep regret that the convention against apartheid
has not yet been ratified (by South Africa) despite the fact that
it is the significant foundation of our new democratic
government," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It dates back to 1976, and the previous government whose main
pillar was apartheid or racial discrimination could neither sign
or ratify the convention, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
