<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda to Resume Cobalt Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A Ugandan government official said
his country is to resume cobalt exports.
</P>
<P>
Kabagambe Kaliisa, permanent secretary of the Ministry of
Energy and Mineral Development, said the first consignment of 23
metric tons of cobalt cathode would be exported to Japan, adding
that the exports will be the first in 22 years for the country, a
press report said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 120-million-U.S-dollar cobalt factory is a joint venture
between the state owned Kilembe Mines Limited and Canadian
Conglomerate Banff Resources. It started producing the metal used
in the manufacture of aircraft on June 24 this year.
</P>
<P>
The cobalt factory, located in Kasese district in western
Uganda, is expected to produce about 1,000 metric tons of the
metal annually, Kaliisa said.
</P>
<P>
When the cobalt exports reach their peak later this year, they
will become Uganda's second biggest foreign exchange earner after
coffee, said the permanent secretary who is also chairman of the
board of directors of the Kasese Cobalt Company Limited. 
</P>
</TEXT>
