<HEADLINE> Highlights of Diplomatic News Today (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of
diplomatic news released by Xinhua today:
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin Meets New Zealand PM
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin said here today that he will be
very glad to pay a state visit to New Zealand this September and
is expecting to explore new ways for bilateral cooperation with
leaders of that country.
</P>
<P>
This effort will be aimed at forging friendly cooperative
relations between the two nations for the next century, Jiang said
while meeting with visiting New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny
Shipley this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
High-level exchanges of visits and contacts have been frequent,
he said, adding that bilateral friendly and mutually beneficial
cooperation has good prospects.
</P>
<P>
Shipley stressed that her visit is intended to further promote
the close and friendly relations of cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
She said her government and people will give Jiang a warm
welcome during his September state visit to New Zealand, which she
is convinced will exert a positive and far-reaching impact on
furthering bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"China is ready to work with New Zealand to make due
contributions to the healthy development of this organization," he
said, adding that he wishes the forthcoming meeting complete
success.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand PM: No Change in "One-China" Policy
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Prime Minister Jenny Shipley said at a press
conference here today that New Zealand government's "one-China"
stand is "unequivocal" and it will not change in the future.
</P>
<P>
Shipley, also Chair of Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC)
this year, also assured that APEC will not change its usual stand
on the Taiwan issue, and its "one-China" policy will continue.
</P>
<P>
Shipley said her current trip is aimed at discussing bilateral
relations and preparing for the upcoming APEC Leadership Informal
Meeting in Auckland in September.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very pleased to be back in China," said Shipley, who last
came here to attend the Fourth World Women's Conference in her
capacity as New Zealand's Minister for Women's Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"The relationship between New Zealand and China is excellent,"
she said. "We are finding opportunities constantly to further
explore the relationship."
</P>
<P>
She said she was "delighted" to have held "very useful" talks
with Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji on a series of serious issues,
including a number of trade areas that have witnessed rapid
development, and some problem areas.
</P>
<P>
Shipley expressed her satisfaction with the consensus reached
on increasing exchange and cooperation in trade, investment,
education, tourism, and other fields.
</P>
<P>
Shipley also expressed her gratitude to China for its support
of the keynote idea of "providing opportunity for building
business" which will highlight the September meeting.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand people are awaiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin'
s upcoming visit," she said.
</P>
