<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Than Hundred Raccoons Killed for Fear of Rabies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Canadian trappers have killed 180
raccoons and 14 skunks in fear of spread of rabies first
discovered a few days ago.
</P>
<P>
Eight trappers are working day and night to kill every raccoon,
skunk and fox within a 75-square-kilometer area in Prescott south
of Ottawa, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a "buffer zone" is being created in the surrounding
area of 225 square kilometers, where another seven trappers are
busy vaccinating every raccoon they've caught.
</P>
<P>
The "Ottawa Citizen" newspaper Monday quoted the Ministry of
Natural Resources as saying that the first case of raccoon rabies
in Canada was detected last Wednesday 10 kilometers north of the
U.S. border.
</P>
<P>
Under the "Operation Point Control" of the ministry, an
estimated 400 raccoons will be killed and another 1,000
vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
Raccoons, infamous for scavenging in garbage bags, could spread
the deadly disease of rabies to humans. Costs associated with
dealing with raccoon rabies in the United States are between 100
million Canadian dollars (about 68 million U.S. dollars) and 300
million (about 204 million U.S. dollars) every year.
</P>
<P>
The last person to die from rabies in Canada was an Alberta man
in 1986. There have been no known cases of humans contracting
raccoon-strain rabies ever since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
