<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Somalia-China Trade Flourishes Amid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"It is the reasonable price of the Chinese commodities that
attract the people and they can afford it," said Ali Baraf.
</P>
<P>
As you enter the Bakara market, the first things you see are
the Chinese White Elephant and Tiger-Head radio batteries, and
next to them lie Chinese-made torches and lamps. As you move a
bit forward you can see the plastic sandals, soap, footballs,
suitcases, bed sheets, shoe polishes and vacuum flasks. Just as
you go a bit deeper you can see the colorful balances and pressure
lanterns.
</P>
<P>
In the electronic wards, almost all of the equipment belong to
China and other few Asian countries. Just name it, the radio
transistors, tape recorders, electric fans, color televisions,
computers, telephone sets, cellular mobile telephones and watches
are all from China.
</P>
<P>
But don't forget the children's world where most of the toys
are also from China, beginning from the wheelchairs for the
children to learn how to walk, equipped with the electronic sound
devices -- toy pistols, machine guns, cars, ambulances, the smart
learning boards, dolls and other beautiful toys.
</P>
<P>
People go through these commodities to buy their favorite at a
price that can be managed by the largely unemployed Somalis.
Still the business is not only in Bakara market, but also in the
chemists and pharmacies. You can find that most of the medicines
are also from China, from the widely consumed antibiotics,
bandages, massages against cold and flu and multi- vitamin drugs
including those equipped with the famous Ginseng.
</P>
<P>
Even though the economy of Somalia is now super decentralized
due to the lack of a central government and a central bank, still
some businessmen can estimate the amount of money involved in the
business with China.
</P>
<P>
"I spent 185,000 US dollars on business with China through
License of Commerce during the first half of this year," said Abdi
Mohamed Ali, who added that apart from his firm there are more
than 30 other firms doing the same as his.
</P>
<P>
"This makes more than 5.5 million dollars per annum," Ali
added. He said all those goods pass through the United Arab of
Emirates on their way to Somalia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
