<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Somalia-China Trade Flourishes Amid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"For instance, I bought two large containers of plastic sandals
with 45, 000 dollars early this year and now a month ago I bought
the same commodity with only 42,000 dollars," said Trabune.
</P>
<P>
For some unclear reasons, the Somalis seem to trust the
Chinese more than any other country. One reason could probably be
the valid traces left behind by China during its collaboration
with the late regime. Almost all of those institutions built by
other friendly countries have been destroyed, except those built
by China. "It is the population of the two countries who in the
end benefit from any relation set up by any political organ or a
government," said Abdullahi Fataho, a Somali politician in
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
A tangible evidence is that even though Somalia's regime had
been toppled and all major facilities destroyed, still those built
by China remain intact, they include the main soccer stadium of
Mogadishu, the main maternity hospital of the capital (Benadir
Hospital), the main tarmac road linking Mogadishu to Baidoa, and
other main tarmac roads from the central regions to the northeast
and northwest of the country. All those facilities built by China
are still operational.
</P>
<P>
However, the only known facility built by China and destroyed
during the civil war is the National Theater. Many people regret
that it was destroyed just because of its beauty and architectural
designs. As long as those premises operate, the Somalia-China
relations will further exist and flourish since the people still
have goods marked at their bottoms "Made In the People's Republic
of China". 
</P>
</TEXT>
