<HEADLINE> Indonesian Commission Yet to Ratify Election Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's General Election
Commission (KPU) is yet to ratify the election results, despite
receipt of the final report on the vote count and tabulation of
the June 7 general election.
</P>
<P>
The KPU is still awaiting the conclusion of the Team of Eleven
whether the election has been free and fair, KPU Chairman Rudini
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Team of Eleven is tasked with formulating views on the
finalization of the results of the 1999 election by the
commission.
</P>
<P>
"KPU officially received the final vote count by the Indonesian
Election Committee (PPI) on Saturday and copies have been sent to
commission members," Rudini told reporters following a plenary
session of the agency.
</P>
<P>
Rudini said that the commission has set July 26 as the new
deadline for announcing the election results.
</P>
<P>
"I have suggested that the ratification of the election results
be done by July 26 for immediate publication, said Rudini.
</P>
<P>
He also disclosed that the allocation of legislative seats
according to the election results can only be started early in
August.
</P>
<P>
The PPI has completed the national tabulation on July 15. Data
from the PPI showed the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle
winning the election with 33.74 percent, and the ruling Golkar
Party trailed behind with 22.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
The PPI elections returns are tentative because the final
results will be issued by the KPU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
