<HEADLINE> Chirac to Visit Four African States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac will
pay a visit to four African states from Wednesday till Sunday to
maintain and expand the political influence of France in sub-
Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
French presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna said that the
visit will be made under the banner of "friendship, openness,
peace and modernization" marking the relationship between France
and Africa.
</P>
<P>
Chirac will promise the leaders of Guinea, Togo, Nigeria and
Cameroon that France will continue to plead for international
economic aid to Africa in international creditors' clubs, said
Colonna.
</P>
<P>
He will also discuss with African leaders the building of
democratic systems and the rule of law in Africa, said the
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
The visit to Nigeria will be the highlight of the tour, as this
will be the first time for a French head of state to visit Nigeria,
Africa's most populous English-speaking country.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, France has become the second largest
buyer of Nigerian products and Nigeria's third largest importer.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Togo, Chirac will congratulate Togolese
President Gnassingbe Eyadema on his success in mediating a peace
treaty in neighboring Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The French president supports the pioneering mechanism of
mediation used by Togo in Sierra Leone, which was jointly
established by the European Union (EU), the French-speaking
community, and the governments of France and Germany for promoting
internal dialogue between conflicting African states and parties.
</P>
<P>
They could also discuss a possible resumption of economic aid
by EU to Togo, which was suspended in 1993 by Brussels for Lome's
"insufficient progress in the field of democracy."
</P>
<P>
In Guinea, the French president will inaugurate with Guinean
President Lansana Conte the Dam on the river of Garafiri, which
was completed with French financing after the World Bank and the
African Development Bank withdrew from the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
