<HEADLINE> Ivanov: Russia-NATO Permanent Council May Resume Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov said here Monday "consultations are being prepared on the
resumption of work by the Russia-NATO Permanent Council."
</P>
<P>
Such contacts "have to do primarily with the Russian
peacekeepers' participation in the international operation in
Kosovo," the Interfax news agency quoted him as saying at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
"Preliminary consultations in a broader context on the
principles of further dealings between Russia and NATO are also
possible," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia suspended its cooperation with NATO after the military
bloc launched a 78-day air campaign against Yugoslavia on March 24.
Limited contacts resumed last month but were restricted to
consultations on cooperation in peacekeeping operations in the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Under a deal reached in Helsinki, Finland, Russia will
eventually deploy 3,600 troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference, Ivanov also commented on the "6 plus
2" meeting on Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The meeting of deputy foreign ministers from China, Iran,
Pakistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan, the six
countries bordering Afghanistan, and Russia and the United States,
"marks an important stage in the search for a political settlement
of the Afghan problem," Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
Both sides of the warring parties in Afghanistan, the Taliban
movement and the United Front, were participating in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The Afghan problem cannot be settled by military means," said
Ivanov, "It's important that the conflicting sides sit down at the
negotiating table and put an end to violence and create political
mechanisms for normalizing the situation." 
</P>
</TEXT>
