<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 Iraqis Killed in U.S., British Bombardment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The number of Iraqi civilians
killed in Sunday's U.S.-British bombardment has risen to 17, the
Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
This was the heaviest civilian casualty in 1999 in U.S.-British
regular attacks on Iraqi civilian and military targets in the two
no-fly zones in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Earlier INA reports quoted an Iraqi military spokesman as
saying on Sunday evening that 14 Iraqi civilians were killed and
17 others injured in the day when warplanes of the United States
and Britain bombed civilian buildings in southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A number of houses at Manathera sub-district in the southern
province of Najaf, 200 kilometers to the south of Baghdad, were
also destroyed in the raid, said INA.
</P>
<P>
A funeral procession was held on Monday morning for the
victims in Najaf province, INA added.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the U.S. and Britain launched four nights of
airstrikes against Iraq, killing hundreds of Iraqi civilians and
soldiers and injured thousands of others.
</P>
<P>
Since the bombardment, Iraq has declared that it does not
recognize the two no-fly zones unilaterally set up by the western
allies and vows to fire at any planes violating its airspace.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were carved up by the U.S.-led western allies
in the wake of the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south from possible attacks by the government troops.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the U.S. and British warplanes have made more than
10,200 sorties over the northern and southern no-fly zones in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Their regular attacks on Iraqi civilian and military targets
have caused severe civilian casualties and property damages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
