<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workshop on Anchovy Fisheries to Be Held in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A workshop on anchovy fisheries in
the Gulf of Thailand will be held in Cha-am, a coastal city 170
kilometers southwest of Bangkok, from Wednesday to Friday this
week, a press release from the United Nations Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is co-organized by the Department of Fisheries of
Thailand's Ministry of Agriculture and Cooperatives and FAO's
regional office in Asia and the Pacific (RAP).
</P>
<P>
About 80 participants are expected to attend the meeting,
including province governors, provincial fisheries officers around
the gulf, small-scale fishermen, representatives from the fish
processing sector and experts in this field.
</P>
<P>
The workshop will review the existing knowledge on anchovy
resources and their exploitation in the Gulf of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Anchovy fisheries have become a hot issue these two months as
some small-scale fishermen in the south blocked the Songkhla deep
sea port for days last month to protest the use of luring light to
catch anchovy nearshore, which is believed to have damaged coastal
resources.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Agriculture Ministry announced a ban on the
use of light for anchovy fishing later last month.
</P>
<P>
FAO's regional office in Bangkok, after receiving an appeal
from small-scale fishermen's organization in the south, decided to
organize the workshop to find solutions to anchovy fisheries in
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The resulting recommendations of the workshop will be forwarded
to the Thai government for further consideration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
