<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Breweries Have Poor Accounting Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- China's most profitable breweries
are plagued with a loophole-ridden accounting system, the Ministry
of Finance revealed in a report today.
</P>
<P>
According to the results of a survey, the ministry conducted
among 110 breweries over the first half of the year, over 92
percent of them have various problems in calculating income, costs,
and profits.
</P>
<P>
Finance Ministry spokesman Wang Jun said here today that the
breweries made false accounts of more than 2.4 billion yuan (about
300 million U.S. dollars) worth of income and costs, and 1.4
billion yuan (about 170 million U.S. dollars) worth of profits.
</P>
<P>
He said that most of the breweries surveyed have weak
accounting systems. "There are many loopholes in the accounting
systems," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some of the breweries have seriously violated
relevant State regulations and laws in this respect.
</P>
<P>
For example, Kouzi Group Corp. of Anhui Province in east China
reported a net profit of 1.14 million yuan last year. However, the
Finance Ministry found that it actually lost more than 22 million
yuan in 1998.
</P>
<P>
An advertising company under the Qufu City Distillery of
Shandong Province in east China deliberately destroyed some
account books and original vouchers.
</P>
<P>
The Songhe Distillery of Henan Province in central China used
illegal original vouchers to withdraw more than 800,000 yuan in
cash in a single month in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Yanghe Distillery and its subordinate companies failed to
put into account more than 100 million yuan worth of sales revenue.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance named a dozen breweries that violated
State laws and regulations in its Report on the Quality of
Accounting Information, released today.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the ministry has been dealing with these
breweries and has asked authorities to mete out legal and
administrative punishment to the people involved.
</P>
<P>
The brewage industry has been one of the most profitable
industries in China. For example, taxes from alcoholic drinks
accounted for one-tenth of the country's total tax revenue in
January this year, growing more than 40 percent over the same
period of last year.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase tax and establish a modern management
system among Chinese breweries, the government is stepping up its
drive to help reform and supervise the companies' financial
systems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
