<HEADLINE> China Announces New Format for Overseas Listing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The China Securities Regulatory
Commission (CSRC) today announced major changes in the approval of
overseas listing by Chinese enterprises.
</P>
<P>
One of these changes provides that overseas listing will no
longer be approved in annual batches, but instead, enterprises can
apply and be approved at anytime, if they are deemed to be
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
The other major change is that, along with state-owned
enterprises, the government said explicitly for the first time
that it supports companies in other forms of ownership in their
bids to be listed in overseas stock markets.
</P>
<P>
According to Chen Yongmin, a CSRC official, 45 Chinese
companies have been listed overseas, raising a total of 10.8
billion U.S. dollars. Among them, the Guangdong Kelong Electrical
Co., Ltd., a leading cooling equipment producer, is the only non-
state enterprise.  
</P>
</TEXT>
