<HEADLINE> Tourism Booming in Anhui </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Anhui Province in east China has
seen a strong surge in tourism this year, receiving a total of 70,
000 overseas and 1.87 million domestic visitors between January
and May.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that some 58,000 overseas tourists
visited Huangshan, one of the most well-known tourist attractions
in the country, during those months, up 37 percent over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Tourism contributed 4.2 percent, or 70 million U.S. dollars, to
the local GDP in 1998, compared to only 0.97 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Anhui boasts five State-class scenic spots including the
renowned resorts of Huangshan, Jiuhuashan, Tianzhushan, Langyashan,
and Qiyunshan.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the province has three State-class historical and
cultural counties, and 23 State-class forest parks, ranking first
in the country.
</P>
<P>
To boost tourism development, the province has given priority
to developing infrastructure facilities. To date, Anhui has
developed 183 hotels for overseas visitors and 187 travel agencies.
Air traffic, railways, and express highways have also been greatly
improved.
</P>
<P>
According to provincial officials, tourism is expected to
contribute five percent to the local GDP by the year 2010.
</P>
</TEXT>
