<HEADLINE> Greece for Dialogue With Turkey to Reduce Tension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Greek Foreign Minister George
Papandreou expressed the hope that the dialogue between Greece and
Turkey next week will reduce tension and give rise to greater
rapprochement between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that this process will be able to first of all reduce
tension," Papandreou said in an interview with the Athens daily "
Eleftherotypia" published on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Later June, Papandreou and his Turkish counterpart, Ismail Cem,
agreed during their talks in New York on establishing committees
of senior diplomats to investigate the possibility of cooperation
on the issues of culture, tourism, environment, illegal
immigration, terrorism, drug trafficking, cross-border crime,
trade, economy and regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Senior foreign ministry officials of Greece and Turkey will
meet on July 26 and 27 to begin the nine-point dialogue.
</P>
<P>
While describing the dialogue as one on matters in which Greece
considered there was a field of common interest, Papandreou said
that issues were not included on which there were diametrically
differing views, such as Turkey's claims in the Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
He noted that such a dialogue could not touch on issues that
pertain to Greece's national sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
For decades, Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have been at
odds for their disputes in the territorial waters, air space
limits and the delimitation of the continental shelf in the Aegean
Sea, and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Greece has repeatedly said that Turkey should take its
unilateral claims to questioning Greek sovereignty over a number
of uninhabited islets in the eastern Aegean to the International
Court of Justice at the Hague, but Turkey refused to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
