<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Govt to Punish Illegal Diamond Miners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Luanda will severely punish illegal
diamond miners in Angola's central Bie Province, where the armed
fighting between the government and the rebel UNITA movement is
one of the fiercest, Sources from the Ministry of Geology and
Mines said.
</P>
<P>
The official Angola Daily Monday said following rumors that
diamond mines of rich reserves were discovered in Bie Province, a
large number of illegal miners have started mining in areas
controlled both by the National Union for the Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA) and the government.
</P>
<P>
Officials from relevant government departments have been sent
to the province for investigation, said the sources, adding once
the rumor is confirmed, the individuals or groups engaged in
illegal diamond mining will be punished according to law.
</P>
<P>
Angolan law rules that diamond is one of the strategic
resources which should remain strictly under government control.
Its prospecting and exploitation must be approved through the
issue of government licenses.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here said the reason why government attaches so much
importance to the illegal mining in Bie is that it is worried that
the diamonds might get into the hands of UNIYA rebels.
</P>
<P>
Angola is one of the major diamond-producing countries in
Africa. The traditional diamond-producing area is in Lunda-Norte
Province in the northeast where about two million carat of diamond
were turned out in 1998, fetching 450 million U.S. dollars in
foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
But according to government estimates, UNITA's smuggling of
diamond to the international market could fetch several hundred
millions of dollars in revenue, which would be used for the
purchase of weaponry and logistic goods to sustain UNITA's
fighting with the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
