<HEADLINE> Lee Teng-hui's Attempt to Split China Is Bound to Fail: Jiang Enzhu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Lee Teng-hui's attempt to split
China has aroused immense indignation among the Chinese people at
home and abroad and his attempt is bound to fail, said Jiang Enzhu,
director of the Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting for the formation of the Hong Kong
Compatriots Preparatory Committee for the Celebration of the 50th
Anniversary of the Founding of the People's Republic of China,
Director Jiang said that Lee Teng-hui's flagrant description of
the cross-straits relations as "state-to-state" is a very
dangerous step towards splitting the country, a serious
provocation to the "one China" principle recognized by the
international community.
</P>
<P>
"This further reveals his nature of splitting China's territory
and sovereignty and separating Taiwan from China," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
This divisive act of Lee Teng-hui has seriously damaged the
basis of the cross-straits relations, affected the stability of
the Taiwan Straits situation, harmed the peaceful reunification
process and therefore aroused great indignation among the Chinese
people at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
In the past few days, people from various circles here in Hong
Kong have come forward to denounce Lee's perverse action, fully
expressing the common aspiration of the Hong Kong compatriots to
resolutely safeguard China's sovereignty and territorial integrity,
to oppose splittism and promote the peaceful reunification of the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
"There is only one China in the world and Taiwan is part of
China. We are firmly opposed to any remarks and acts aimed at
creating 'two Chinas,' 'one China, one Taiwan' and 'Taiwan
independence'," Jiang declared.
</P>
<P>
To solve the Taiwan issue and realize the complete
reunification of the motherland is the sacred task of the entire
Chinese people and the irreversible trend of history, and Lee Teng-
hui's attempt to split the motherland is bound to fail, he
concluded. 
</P>
