<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Airbus Optimistic About Asia-Pacific Market Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- An Airbus Industrie market
forecast shows that the Asia-Pacific air transport market is
expected to generate demand for more than 4,300 passenger aircraft
valued at over 450 billion U.S. dollars over the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
In terms of aircraft numbers, this represents almost a quarter
of the European aircraft manufacturer's forecast world demand for
passenger aircraft between now and 2018, said the forecast report.
</P>
<P>
Adam Brown, Airbus Industrie Vice President Forecasting and
Strategic Planning, told Hong Kong media Monday that despite the
effects of the recent downturn on airline performance, underlying
fundamentals all point towards recovery for the industry within
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
"Airbus Industrie remains extremely optimistic about the medium
and long-term prospects for Asian air travel," he said. "In fact,
we predict that the 52 largest airlines in the region will lead
the world in terms of overall growth in capacity over the next 20
years, to the point where they will be flying as many as the
airlines of Europe by the Year 2018."
</P>
<P>
According to the study, which takes into account a recovery
period of reduced growth between now and 2001, overall passenger
traffic in the region will rise at an annual average rate of 6.1
percent for the 20 years to 2018. This compares with a world
average of 5 percent each year.
</P>
<P>
In order to meet this growth, available seat capacity in the
Asia-Pacific region will need to rise from the current level of
442,000, or 24 percent of global capacity, to over 1.2 million, or
30 percent of all available airline seats worldwide.
</P>
<P>
As a result, over 2,400 aircraft will be required by Asia-
Pacific airlines purely to meet growth requirements.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, almost all of the current in-service fleet of
just under 1,900 aircraft will also be replaced over the forecast
period, increasing the total market potential to the predicted
level of some 4,300 units.
</P>
<P>
In terms of aircraft size, Airbus Industrie forecast predicts
that the Asia-Pacific region will continue to be a key market for
the 300, 350 and 400 seaters, with a requirement for some 1,150
aircraft in the categories served the best-selling A330/A340
family.
</P>
<P>
Brown said that the Asia-Pacific region will also continue to
drive the development of new, very large aircraft for the 21st
century, with a requirement in the region for just over 660
aircraft larger than anything flying today.
</P>
<P>
This represents over half of the total predicted world demand
for some 1,200 units in this size category over the next 20 years,
which will be met by aircraft such as the new 480-600 seat A3XX
family now under study at Airbus Industrie, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
