<HEADLINE> China Bans Abuse of National Day Celebrations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Profit-seeking activities which
abuse the name of national day celebrations have been banned
across China in order to relieve the burdens on enterprises being
harassed by fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
The general offices of the Communist Party of China (CPC)
Central Committee and the State Council jointly issued a circular
today which prohibits individuals and units from collecting fees,
asking for financial support, or canvassing advertisements from
enterprises before the 50th anniversary of the founding of the
People's Republic of China on October 1.
</P>
<P>
"Some press and publication units, and governmental and social
organizations have been pressing enterprises to pay for
publications, television programs, and exhibitions as gifts for
the nation's birthday," the circular said.
</P>
<P>
Some profit-seekers even produced souvenirs and presents for
the celebrations and have abused the national flag and emblem by
putting them on products, it said.
</P>
<P>
"These activities go against relevant regulations of the CPC
Central Committee and the central government and have brought
about adverse effects," it added. "They should be stopped
immediately."
</P>
<P>
The central government has repeatedly warned local governments
and organizations to avoid extravagance and waste while preparing
for the celebrations in October.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
