<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Somalia-China Trade Flourishes Amid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"It is the reasonable price of the Chinese commodities that
attract the people and they can afford it," said Ali Baraf.
</P>
<P>
As you enter the Bakara market, the first things you see are
the Chinese White Elephant and Tiger-Head radio batteries, and
next to them lie Chinese-made torches and lamps. As you move a
bit forward you can see the plastic sandals, soap, footballs,
suitcases, bed sheets, shoe polishes and vacuum flasks. Just as
you go a bit deeper you can see the colorful balances and pressure
lanterns.
</P>
<P>
In the electronic wards, almost all of the equipment belong to
China and other few Asian countries. Just name it, the radio
transistors, tape recorders, electric fans, color televisions,
computers, telephone sets, cellular mobile telephones and watches
are all from China.
</P>
<P>
But don't forget the children's world where most of the toys
are also from China, beginning from the wheelchairs for the
children to learn how to walk, equipped with the electronic sound
devices -- pistols, machine guns, cars, ambulances, the smart
learning boards, dolls and other beautiful toys.
</P>
<P>
People go through these commodities to buy their favorite at a
price that can be managed by the largely unemployed Somalis.
Still the business is not only in Bakara market, but also in the
chemists and pharmacies. You can find that most of the medicines
are also from China, from the widely consumed antibiotics,
bandages, massages against cold and flu and multi- vitamin drugs
including those equipped with the famous Ginseng.
</P>
<P>
Even though the economy of Somalia is now super decentralized
due to the lack of a central government and a central bank, still
some businessmen can estimate the amount of money involved in the
business with China.
</P>
<P>
"I spent 185,000 US dollars on business with China through
License of Commerce during the first half of this year," said Abdi
Mohamed Ali, who added that apart from his firm there are more
than 30 other firms doing the same as his.
</P>
<P>
"This makes more than 5.5 million dollars per annum," Ali
added. He said all those goods pass through the United Arab of
Emirates on their way to Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Another fascinating thing is said to be the ever-cheapening
prices of the commodities imported from China, according to
Somali businessmen Muhidin Trabune, a large store owner in Bakara
market. He said the prices never stay the same in China for three
months. It is always cheaper than before.
</P>
<P>
"For instance, I bought two large containers of plastic sandals
with 45, 000 dollars early this year and now a month ago I bought
the same commodity with only 42,000 dollars," said Trabune.
</P>
<P>
For some unclear reasons, the Somalis seem to trust the
Chinese more than any other country. One reason could probably be
the valid traces left behind by China during its collaboration
with the late regime. Almost all of those institutions built by
other friendly countries have been destroyed, except those built
by China. "It is the population of the two countries who in the
end benefit from any relation set up by any political organ or a
government," said Abdullahi Fataho, a Somali politician in
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
A tangible evidence is that even though Somalia's regime had
been toppled and all major facilities destroyed, still those built
by China remain intact, they include the main soccer stadium of
Mogadishu, the main maternity hospital of the capital (Benadir
Hospital), the main tarmac road linking Mogadishu to Baidoa, and
other main tarmac roads from the central regions to the northeast
and northwest of the country. All those facilities built by China
are still operational.
</P>
<P>
However, the only known facility built by China and destroyed
during the civil war is the National Theater. Many people regret
that it was destroyed just because of its beauty and architectural
designs. As long as those premises operate, the Somalia-China
relations will further exist and flourish since the people still
have goods marked at their bottoms "Made In the People's Republic
of China". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elf Launches Counter Takeover Bid Against Total-Fina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The French oil group Elf-Aquitaine
launched on Monday a dramatic counter takeover bid against its
French-Belgian rival, Total-Fina, plunging the two best known
French industrial groups into a gigantic summer merger battle.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Officer of Elf-Aquitaine, Philippe Jaffre, made
the announcement at a press conference, two weeks after Total Fina
's chairman Thierry Desmarest staged a hostile take-over bid to
absorb Elf.
</P>
<P>
A merger either way between the two oil groups would result in
the world's fourth biggest oil and gas group and its fifth biggest
chemicals group.
</P>
<P>
Elf offers to exchange five shares of Total-Fina with every
three of its own shares, or buy every five shares of Total-Fina
with 190 euros (192 U.S. dollars) in cash.
</P>
<P>
The administration council of Elf said that it would launch a "
renewing industrial project" dividing a resulting entity into
separate oil and gas and chemical businesses.
</P>
<P>
The annual pretax synergies of a merged group are estimated at
2.5 billion euros (2.525 billion U.S. dollars) in three years,
more than twice the 1.2 billion euros as estimated by Total-Fina.
</P>
<P>
Elf said that its offer would give a 10 percent premium ex
dividend to the French-Belgian group's closing price on Friday.
</P>
<P>
This puts the value of Total-Fina at 50.3 billion euros (50.8
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Elf predicts that a merger with Total-Fina would result in the
downsizing of 6,000 jobs, including 2,000 in France, while Total
said that it would cut down 4,000 jobs if it took over Elf.
</P>
<P>
Elf now employs 85,000 people, and Total-Fina 71,600.
</P>
<P>
Total-Fina announced on July 5 that it offers four shares of
its own for three shares of Elf, which puts the value of Elf at 42
billion euros (42.42 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A counter take-over bid was the only choice for Elf, because an
alliance with a foreign oil group will be surely opposed by the
French government which has a right of veto, called "golden share.
" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
