<HEADLINE> Chinese, Australian Youth Asked to Contribute to Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Jiang Chunyun, vice-chairman of
the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress (NPC),
today called on both Chinese and Australian youth to contribute to
the growth of bilateral ties by increasing mutual understanding
and exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by Jiang, who is also a member of the
Political Bureau of the Communist Party of China Central Committee,
in a meeting with a delegation from the Australian Political
Exchange Council led by Judi Moylan, a member of the Australian
Federal Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Political Exchange Council, established in 1981,
is intended to promote exchanges between young political leaders
in Australia and the rest of the world so as to help them have a
better understanding of the international issues.
</P>
<P>
Before visiting Beijing, the Australian delegation, together
with Chinese young leaders, attended a two-day seminar held in
Chengdu, capital of southwest China's Sichuan province.
</P>
<P>
During the gathering, participants agreed that the maintenance
and development of healthy, stable and constructive Sino-
Australian relationship accord with the fundamental interests of
both peoples, and will also serve to safeguard peace, stability
and development in the Asia-Pacific region and the world.
</P>
<P>
They also believed that young people of the two countries
shoulder responsibilities for promoting Sino-Australian ties.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the delegation members talked about the
impression of their ongoing China visit. They said that the visit
enabled them to have a better understanding of China. 
</P>
