<HEADLINE> Nigerian Speaker's Fate to Be Determined Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The fate of Alhaji Ibrahim Buhari,
Nigerian Speaker of the House of Representative, would be
determined Tuesday as both the upper and lower houses reconvene.
</P>
<P>
As calls for the resignation of the speaker mount, Buhari is to
file a suit Monday at a Lagos High Court against the Independent
Communications Network Limited, publishers of The News magazine.
</P>
<P>
The News magazine published on July 11 alleged that Buhari is
29 and not the 36 years of age he claims to be, and that he never
attended the University of Toronto in Canada which he also claims
to be an alumnus.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the speaker's lawyer Chief Ladi Williams gave the
publishers a 72-hour ultimatum to retract their story and
apologize to the speaker on their story in which their magazine
accused Buhari of forgery.
</P>
<P>
However, leaders of the ruling People's Democratic Party (PDP)
of which the speaker is a member have advised Buhari to step aside
quietly to save the reputation of the party.
</P>
<P>
Chief Solomon Lar, national chairman of the ruling party, had
been holding a series of consultations with party leaders on the
issue to see how the party could salvage the situation.
</P>
<P>
Party sources said that the PDP leadership had resolved to
force Buhari out of the party if the allegations were confirmed.
</P>
<P>
It was learnt that the expulsion option was considered against
the backdrop of Buhari's vow to stay on in office and the fact
that it might be difficult to prosecute a successful impeachment
process against the speaker as he is said to enjoy the support of
the majority of the members.
</P>
<P>
A lobby team of the National Assembly whose members are from
the northern part of the country has been set up to save Buhari's
political career, saying that the allegations against Buhari were
part of a grand design to disgrace the north and deny it of the
position of Speaker of the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, senators of the opposition Alliance for Democracy
(AD) and members of the House of Representatives have begun
independent investigations into the allegations against the
speaker.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Senate's Establishment Committee Otunba
Durojaiye described the allegations as an embarrassment to the law
makers, especially as a bill to fight corruption and other vices
was before the assembly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
