<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Group Says Settlements Flourish Since 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Jewish settlement activities
have flourished since 1996 with 42 satellite settlements set up in
the occupied territories, a study conducted by Israel's Peace Now
movement indicates.
</P>
<P>
The study shows that 20 of the 42 new settlements are within
1,000 meters of their mother settlements, the local daily Haaretz
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, 13 are between 1,000 and 2,500 meters away and four
are more than 2.5 kilometers from their mother settlements.
</P>
<P>
The study shows that the majority of these settlements were
built without official permission, but were later approved by
former prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu and former defense
minister Moshe Arens.
</P>
<P>
Peace Now members complained that the new government led by
Prime Minister Ehud Barak is following in Netanyahu's footsteps
by ignoring complaints made against settlements.
</P>
<P>
After his victory in the May elections, Barak pledged to stop
building new settlements and solve the settlement issue with the
Palestinians in the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
However, during the coalition negotiations, Barak reportedly
promised Yisrael Baliyah Party and National Religious Party that
satellite settlements approved by the defense establishment, and
that lie within the official borders of their mother settlements,
will be allowed to remain in place at least until the final
status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Peace Now movement charged that Barak is wasting time to
stop the settlers from establishing irreversible facts on the
ground before the start of final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Peace Now's study is expected to be the basis of a cabinet
discussion next week regarding the future of satellite
settlements, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
The discussion, requested by the left-wing Meretz party, will
use the distance from the mother settlement to its satellite as a
primary criterion for determining the settlement's future.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, data published by Israeli Central Bureau of
Statistics on Sunday showed that the number of Jewish settlers in
the territories has been on the rise.
</P>
<P>
According to the data, 166,100 Jews are living in the West Bank
at the end of 1998, while 6,400 Jews are living in the Gaza Strip,
12 percent more than the figure at the end of 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
