<HEADLINE> Employment Opportunities Improved in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The provisional seasonally
adjusted unemployment rate for the period April-June 1999 in Hong
Kong was 6.1 percent, and the provisional underemployment rate was
2.9 percent, according to statistics released today by the Census
and Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
For the period March-May 1999, the seasonally adjusted
unemployment rate was confirmed to be the same as the previously
released provisional figure of 6.3 percent, while the
underemployment rate was revised upward to 3.0 percent from the
provisional figure of 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the period April-June 1999 with March-May 1999,
decreases in unemployment rate were seen mainly in the
construction, manufacturing, import/export trades, hotels,
transport, real estate and insurance sectors.
</P>
<P>
As to the underemployment rate, decreases were seen in the
decoration and maintenance, manufacturing, transport and
restaurants sectors.
</P>
<P>
K.Y. Tang, the government economist, observed that as business
conditions gradually improved, the labor market also benefited,
and both the unemployment and the underemployment rates fell in
the most recent period.
</P>
<P>
However, he cautioned that with more fresh graduates and school
leavers entering the labor market in the next couple of months,
the unemployment rate especially for younger persons would
probably remain relatively high in the near term. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Attaches Importance to Farm Input </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia said Monday it will
increase agricultural input to meet the food requirement of the
ever-increasing population of the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a workshop on the development of agricultural input
supply system in sub-Saharan Africa, Ethiopian Agricultural
Minister Mengistu Hulluka said increased use of modern input such
as improved seeds and fertilizers is of great importance to
agricultural development in African continent.
</P>
<P>
The four-day workshop is sponsored by the United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and the International
Fertilizer Development Center (IFDC).
</P>
<P>
Mengistu called on African countries to pay attention to the
role of government parastatals and private sector with regard to
provision of improved seeds, fertilizers, pesticides and other
inputs to farmers.
</P>
<P>
"African governments should, whenever required, create the
conditions necessary to ensure growth, stability and equitable
access to productive resources as well as to establish a sense of
participation by the farmers themselves and the communities at
large," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia is a country where agriculture plays a vital role in
its national economy. It provides employment to over 85 percent
of the active labor force, and generates over 90 percent of the
export revenue in the country, according to Mengistu.
</P>
<P>
Lalla Ben Barka, ECA deputy executive secretary, also attached
importance to agricultural development in Africa when speaking at
the workshop.
</P>
<P>
Increasing agricultural productivity in Africa on a sustainable
basis will provide the key to a permanent solution to the
continent's food insecurity and poverty problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official also expressed belief that private sector
involvement will play a bigger and bigger role in African
agriculture during the next millennium. 
</P>
