<HEADLINE> Myanmar FM Ends Visit to Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Foreign Minister U Win Aung
left here Monday for home via Bangkok ending a three-day visit to
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the Zia international airport before
his departure, Aung, terming his visit as a "familiarization"
tour, said the visit had enabled him to establish contact with
Bangladeshi leaders and know their mind on different issues.
</P>
<P>
The visit was "useful," and would help strengthen bilateral
relations between the two neighbors, said the Myanmar minister,
who arrived here on Saturday after a visit to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the repatriation of the remaining Myanmar refugees
in Bangladesh, Aung hoped that the problem would be "solved soon."
</P>
<P>
Aung said he was pleased to have met with President Shahabuddin
Ahmed, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina and other Bangladeshi leaders,
adding that this would help bring the two nations closer and forge
better understanding between them.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that some problems still remained between the two
countries, but assured that those would be solved since there was
a "will" on both sides to resolve the problems.
</P>
<P>
Problems between the two neighbors could be solved once a joint
commission between the two countries was formed, and bilateral
relations would also get a boost with the formation of such a
commission, he said.
</P>
<P>
Aung and his Bangladeshi counterpart, Abdus Samad Azad, held
official talks Saturday on bilateral relations, particularly the
repatriation of the over 20,000 Myanmar refugees, known here as
Rohingya refugees, who are living in two camps in Cox's Bazar,
southeast Bangladesh. 
</P>
