<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC Free Trade Deal Back on Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations for the
establishment of a free trade area in the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) by January next year are back on
track, independent news group's Business Report said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The breakthrough came as a result of an agreement between South
African and Zimbabwean trade ministers last week to improve
Zimbabwe's trade quota under the current trade agreement between
the two countries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Mfundo Nkuhlu, chief director of African trade relations in the
South African Department of Trade and Industry, said the agreement
meant the SADC trade protocol could be ratified before the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
"The ratification will probably take place once (South
Africa's) parliament is in session again, and this will mean that
the SADC free trade area would be implemented by January next
year," Nkuhlu was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for a free trade area in the SADC region, which,
if implemented, is expected to create some five million new jobs
in the short term and add 15.7 billion rand (2.6 billion U.S.
dollars) to the region's gross domestic product, began last year.
</P>
<P>
They failed to reach their June deadline after several
contentious issue arose.
</P>
<P>
These included problems with rules of origin, the threatened
deterioration of the trade preferences of South Africa's weaker
partners in the Southern African Customs Union, and, most
importantly, the impasse with Zimbabwe, South Africa's biggest
trading partner in the SADC, over the amount of Zimbabwean goods
granted access to the South African market under the current
bilateral trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Customs Union covers five of the 14
members of the SADC -- South Africa, Namibia, Botswana, Lesotho
and Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
Nkuhlu said this adjustment in the quota allocation was only a
technical one rather than an alteration of the existing agreement.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
