<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Trade News in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of major trade news in
China between July 12 and 18:
</P>
<P>
-- China has so far approved 1,700 foreign-funded
pharmaceutical projects.
</P>
<P>
-- China and Australia reached a consensus in principle on some
major issues about China's entry into the World Trade Organization
(WTO).
</P>
<P>
-- The crackdown on smuggling and tax evasions and import
increases helped China's customs revenues in the first half, which
amounted to 78.36 billion yuan (about 9.44 billion U.S. dollars)
and accounted for 93.4 percent of this year's target.
</P>
<P>
-- China has decided to increase controls on cross-Straits
labor contracts for fishermen after the killing of 11 mainland
crew members on a Taiwanese boat last February and several other
incidents.
</P>
<P>
-- Australia believes that China will "substantially strengthen
the operation" of the WTO when it becomes member of the global
trading system, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said
here last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
-- China and Australia announced here last Tuesday that they
have concluded bilateral negotiations on all issues concerning
China's admission into the WTO.
</P>
<P>
-- Despite a decline of 4.6 percent in the first half of the
year, China's exports showed some signs of recovery during the
period, according to the latest Customs figures.
</P>
