<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates Airline (Emirates) has
signed a five-year contract with the Hong Kong Aero Engine
Services Ltd. (HAESL) for the repair and overhaul of the
carrier's Rolls-Royce Trent engines.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal involving 92 million dirhams (about 25 million
U.S. dollars), HAESL will repair and overhaul all Rolls-Royce
Trent 800 and 700 engines used on Emirates' Boeing 777 and
A330-200 aircrafts, the Gulf News daily reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Emirates currently operates nine Boeing 777-200, and is
expected to own three Boeing 777-300 by the end of 2000. There are
also 18 A330-200 on firm order, three of which have been
delivered, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The African Development Bank has agreed in principle
to provide a loan of 60 million U.S. dollars for Egypt, the
country's Middle East News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to modernize irrigation projects in an
area of 120,000 feddans (50,400 hectares) in the governorate of
Dakahlia, 90 kilometers south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of the bank is due here later this month to sign
an agreement in this regard, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Germany has decided to hold its first exhibition in
Cairo on October 17 to 20, Egypt's Al-Akhbar newspaper reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 German companies are expected to take part in the fair
of hi-tech products.
</P>
<P>
The official said a number of German companies have also agreed
to set up joint ventures in Egypt by transferring expertise and
technology to Egyptian enterprises.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Agreements have been reached for Egypt to export 1,000
tons of ghee to Syria to meet the need of its confectionery
industry, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Ebied, chairman of the Cairo Oils and Soap Company, told
the English-language newspaper that the export is worth 25 million
Egyptian pounds (7.35 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Ebied said Egypt will also sell to Syria 10 million pounds (2.94
million dollars) worth of oils and soap of high quality in the
coming period.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian private sector has set up a company with
a capital of 25 million Egyptian pounds (7.35 million
U.S. dollars) to run the first regular and direct maritime line
between Egypt and East African countries as of August.
</P>
<P>
The new line will link the Red Sea port of Suez, 120 kilometers
east of Cairo, with Djibouti, Mombasa of Kenya, Dar-es Salam of
Tanzania and Mauritius in the Indian Ocean, Egypt's Middle East
News Agency reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The company will put six ships with a total capacity of 40,000
tons on the line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
