<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Raises Tax Rebate Rates for Export Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government announced
today that it will raise tax rebate rates for a wide range of
products for the overseas market.
</P>
<P>
This is seen as a major step to expand exports, which has been
on the decline under the impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Finance and the State Administration of
Taxation (SAT) jointly announced today that the average tax rebate
rate for export-oriented products has been raised by 2.95
percentage points effective on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The tax rebate rate for garments was raised to 17 percent, and
those for textile raw materials and textile products rose to 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
For machinery and electronic products, the rebate rate were
raised to 15 percent, except for four categories of products that
already enjoy tax rebate rates of 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
These four categories include machinery and equipment, electric
appliances and electronic products, transport vehicles, and
instruments and meters.
</P>
<P>
For those products which had a tax rebate rate of only 11 to 13
percent, the tax rebate rate was raised to 15 percent, and
products which had a tax rebate rate of nine percent, now enjoy a
13 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
Except for agricultural products, those products that had a tax
rebate rate of less than 13 percent, have had this rate raised to
13 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result of these increases, China has reduced the total
number of rates from five to four.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
