<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Economy Surges 11.9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Economy in this Chinese capital
city soared a year-on-year 11.9 percent in the first half of this
year, 4.3 percentage points than the national average.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Bureau of Statistics announced today that
the Gross Domestic Product totaled 95.47 billion yuan (about 11.53
billion US dollars) during the first half-year period.
</P>
<P>
Beijing sets its annual economic growth target for 1999 at nine
percent.
</P>
<P>
The fast-paced economy is largely attributable to a remarkable
18.4-percent growth rate in the industrial sector, which chalked
up 38.06 billion yuan (about 4.59 billion U.S. dollars) in added
value in the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
"The series of policies the municipal government has adopted
since last year to increase domestic demand is the major reason
behind the accelerated industrial growth," said Tang Long,
director of the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The service sector, which has maintained two-digit growth for
several years, created 54.12 billion yuan in added value during
the period, up 6.5 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The agricultural sector continued to register stable growth
during the period, bringing in 3.29 billion yuan in added value,
an increase of 2.1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
