<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Stops Nuclear Sailing to Japan After Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 19 (Xinhua) - Britain on Monday was forced to
abandon plans to ship nuclear fuel to Japan after a standoff with
floating environmental activists who strongly protested against it.
</P>
<P>
British Nuclear Fuels Ltd (BNFL) said the Pacific Teal, a ship
scheduled to leave for Japan returned to berth at Barrow, a port
city in northwest England, because of safety concerns sparked by
the overnight protest.
</P>
<P>
Another armed shipment of mixed oxide fuel, which had also been
preparing to leave the port for Japan, where the plutonium fuel
was to be loaded into nuclear power reactors, still remains in the
docks.
</P>
<P>
The Greenpeace environmental group, which staged the protest,
said the two ships' combined cargo could be converted into 60
nuclear bombs.
</P>
<P>
Opponents of the shipments fear environmental fallout,nuclear
proliferation and possible hijacking on the high seas.
</P>
<P>
BNFL denied the plutonium was ever at risk and said the
security arrangements fully satisfied a U.S.-Japan nuclear pact,
under which Tokyo needs U.S. consent to ship plutonium.
</P>
<P>
Local report said seven Greenpeace protesters have been
arrested at the demonstration against the shipments of nuclear
fuel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
