<HEADLINE> China Promoting Digital Library Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- China is introducing digital
techniques into its libraries, so as to give more people access to
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Libraries in Beijing, Shanghai, Shenzhen and Nanjing cities and
Guangdong and Liaoning provinces have been pioneers in this
respect since 1997, according to the China Society of Library
Science.
</P>
<P>
Two libraries in Guangdong have already copied over three
million pages of their documents onto their websites on the www.
163.net and the www.169.net, which are expected to have some two
million visitors each month.
</P>
<P>
Digital science provides the libraries with more room for
further development, experts argue. And it will bring changes not
only to the contemporary library service, but also to its stored
contents. Printed books are only one kind of accumulation of
knowledge resources, while digital science greatly boosts
information sharing.
</P>
<P>
Colleges and universities in China are also trying to make use
of digital science in their libraries. Up to now, over 100 of them
have opened websites.
</P>
<P>
The National Library of Beijing set up its first electronic
reading room in 1996, and the second one in 1997, offering
software and CD data services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
