<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Considers Restoring Countrywide Development Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is
considering restoring the countrywide development funds (CDF) to
be used for pro-poor projects by congressmen in congressional
districts, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said in a statement that the government has generated
enough savings that can be used to allocate 30 million pesos
(750,000 U.S. dollars) per congressional district that will be
identified by lawmakers in the fiscal year 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
He said that legislators will be allowed to identify projects
for government to fund, under their CDF, but these should all
conform with the government's pro-poor programs, to prevent misuse
of the money.
</P>
<P>
In the past, as much as 24 percent of the national budget were
reported to have been lost to graft and corruption. This finding
has prompted the government to abolish the CDF when it submitted
to Congress its proposed budget for 1999.
</P>
<P>
Zamora noted that the proposal is still under serious
consideration by the government, stressing that "if the government
decides to restore the funds, these would go only to hard
infrastructure projects."
</P>
<P>
If restored in the next fiscal year, Zamora said congressmen
and senators will be allowed to decide what projects they would
fund out of their CDF, but these should only involve hard
infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
No figure has yet been given as to how much CDF will be given
to congressmen and senators since the matter is still under study,
Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
He said the restoration of CDF may be necessary since
legislators have complained that they have not been able to
address their constituents' needs after they have been stripped of
the power to identify the projects needed by their congressional
districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
