<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Arctic Expedition Team Adjusts Research Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABOARD THE SNOW DRAGON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Arctic
expedition team has adjusted its research plan to bring forward
its 13-15 day oceanic and fishery resources survey in the Bering
Sea and postpone research in the Arctic Ocean, as a result of
unfavorable weather and ice conditions.
</P>
<P>
The icebreaker Snow Dragon, carrying more than 120 scientists
and journalists, exited the Arctic Sea this morning, having
crossed the Arctic Circle five days ago.
</P>
<P>
The complex, unpredictable weather and ice conditions in the
Arctic Ocean hampered the ship from going further north, said Chen
Liqi, leader and chief scientist of the expedition.
</P>
<P>
The scientists will wait for an improvement in the ice
conditions, and recross the Arctic Circle. The adjustment of the
research plan will help ensure the success of the expedition, Chen
noted.
</P>
<P>
In the previous five days of research in the Chukchi Sea, the
scientists obtained ample, valuable air and water samples.
</P>
<P>
The scientists will proceed to focus on studying the ecological
system in the vicinity of the Arctic Ocean and the biological
resources in the Bering Sea, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
The "Snow Dragon," which had already been used in five Chinese
expeditions to the South Pole, underwent examinations and major
overhauls last year; and it would sail to the South Pole again in
November this year.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, prolonged exposure to the ice-floe area will do
harm to and even damage the vessel, and this is another reason why
the expedition team adjusted its plan, said Chen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chengdu Attracts More Overseas Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Some 82,000 overseas tourists
visited this capital city of southwest China's Sichuan Province in
the first half of this year, up 41 percent over the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xiaoquan, director of the Chengdu City Tourism Bureau,
attributed the increase to a big rise in the number of tourists
from Southeast Asian countries which are recovering from the
region's worst financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest statistics, some 5,200 tourists from
Thailand and 7,200 from Singapore visited the city in the first
six months, compared to over 1,000 and 3,500 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The World Horticulture Exposition in the city of Kunming in the
neighboring Yunnan Province, which started on May 1 and runs
through October 31, was another main contributor to the increase.
</P>
<P>
But he noted that the foreign exchange earned from the tourism
industry during the period increased by only 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
He explained that foreign tourists often stayed in the city for
a short period of time because their destinations were always
scenic spots in other part of the Sichuan province, such as
Mountain Emei, Leshan Buddha and Jiuzhaigou and Huanglong Nature
Reserves.
</P>
<P>
Chengdu has actually served as a transit for them, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
