<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Short of Anti-Malaria Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's health authorities,
battling a devastating malaria outbreak in the country's western
region, are running out of essential medicine.
</P>
<P>
Especially in short supply is the crucial drug quinine, the
backbone of the ministry's fight against the killer tropical
disease, the East African weekly newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the disease had claimed more than 1,000
lives since its outbreak earlier this year, with most of the
victims from Kisii district, Nyanza Province in southwestern
Kenya. However, the government said about 700 people have died so
far.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Health Ministry said, "the Central Supplies
Unit in capital Nairobi has issued all its quinine stocks and
other anti-malaria drugs such as sulphadoxine-pyrimethamine
(metakelfin) are fast running out."
</P>
<P>
In total, the government positioned over 130,000 doses of
quinine in risk districts by April, leaving some 73,000 doses in
stock at the Central Supplied Unit, the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, the government has spent about one
million U. S. dollars on the drugs and their transportation to
malaria-stricken districts.
</P>
<P>
The ministry officials are making much effort to procure new
supplies to combat the epidemic, which has reportedly affected
close to 200,000 people across this east African country.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya National Malaria Control Program is drawing up plans
to seek urgent donor funding to enable it to purchase more drugs
and also to implement vector control strategies, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Assistant Health Minister Abdullahi Wako said last week that
malaria kills 72 children under the age of five everyday and six
million out- patient malaria cases are reported annually in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
