<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Life Insurance Claims Case Settled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- China's largest personal insurance
claims case has been recently settled in Beijing, with the
beneficiaries expected to receive a total of 2.4 million yuan (
about 289,000 U.S. dollars) from the insurer.
</P>
<P>
According to officials at the Taikang Life Insurance Co.,
Limited, the policy holder, who was identified as a Mr. Li, was
insured in 1997 against major diseases and two other liabilities
with a total insured amount of 360,000 yuan, in case of the policy
holder's death.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the insured was found of brain cancer in 1998
and eventually died in February 1999 at the age of 34.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the insurer paid out a total 360,000 yuan to cover
the medical bill and other insured liabilities.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Li also bought several policies for his twin sons,
according to which, the sons would be paid a total of 1.76 million
yuan in 13 years to cover their life and education costs. In
addition to other indemnities, the total amount in the future
would be nearly two million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The insurer has recently paid the twins 120,000 yuan as the
first batch of the claims package.
</P>
<P>
Chen Dongsheng, Taikang Life's General Manager, told reporters
that the timely settlement of any claims is the base for insurers
to won the trust of customers.
</P>
<P>
He added that the case may help raise the public's awareness of
insurance.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Bo, a professor with the Insurance Department of Beijing
University, told Xinhua in an interview that settlement has been a
major source of complaints against insurance companies in China
for a long time, adding that with competition getting more and
more fierce, only those insurers with good credit and services
could expect to expand their market shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
