<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Wants All Illegal Congo (K) Immigrants Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has ordered
the immediate deportation of all nationals of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) who entered the country illegally.
</P>
<P>
Home Affairs Deputy Minister Edwin Hatembo who was on a tour of
Luapula Province in the north said the Immigration department has
powers to deport illegal immigrants without taking them to court.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia newspaper Monday quoted Hatembo as saying after
learning that the Immigration Department in the province was
prosecuting six Congolese nationals who entered the country
illegally.
</P>
<P>
Hatembo said illegal Congolese immigrants detained in Mansa,
northern Zambia, should be taken back to their country to avoid
congestion and shortage of food in prisons.
</P>
<P>
"Considering the short distance from Mansa to the Democratic
Republic of Congo, it is necessary that these people are cleared
because they are not budgeted for," said the deputy minister.
</P>
<P>
Immigration officials told Hatembo after he inspected prisons,
police and National Registration Departments in Mansa that there
were still many refugees entering the country in Kaputa, Northern
Province.
</P>
<P>
Other refugees who infiltrated villages have also started
reporting to Kaputa because of hunger.
</P>
<P>
By Sunday the number of refugees at Kaputa was 4,820 and the
process of transporting them to Mporokoso, also in Northern
Province, was still going on.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, seven Congolese soldiers who were being held in
Mansa demanded to be taken back to their country.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers who had been held in the district for some time
appealed to Hatembo to free them as they were worried about the
welfare of their families in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
Hatembo promised that the government would look into their
plight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
