<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3,000 Zambian Copper Miners to Lose Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- About 3,000 copper miners at Roan
Antelope Mining Corporation will soon lose their jobs in a
trimming exercise aimed at strengthening operations.
</P>
<P>
Both management and Roan branch officials of the Mine-workers
Union of Zambia have confirmed the impending retrenchment
exercise, Zambia Daily Mail reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
This will reduce the work force by about half of the private
copper mine.
</P>
<P>
The list of those to go has already been compiled, said the
Union.
</P>
<P>
"Yes it is true, the list has been compiled. As of now we are
awaiting the next move from the government," said Cameron Pwele,
Roan branch chairman of the Union.
</P>
<P>
Some miners said they are ready to start a new life but
demanded their benefits accrued from the state-run Zambia
Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) before they can stop working.
</P>
<P>
A management official said reducing the work force will make
the operations of the mine viable because currently there are many
problems at the mine.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, negotiations for improved conditions of service for
miners are going on smoothly and the Union said it is confident of
a positive response from the government.
</P>
<P>
In the process of privatization of Zambia's mining industry, a
number of workers have been retrenched and more will be. 
</P>
</TEXT>
