<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Shaanxi To Become Mushroom-Production Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The arid plateau in central Shaanxi
Province in northwest China is hopeful of becoming a new mushroom-
production base in China, with the application of a new technique
developed by agronomists at the Shaanxi Provincial Academy of
Agricultural Sciences.
</P>
<P>
After a one-year experiment, the agronomists have successfully
developed a technique to grow mushrooms using pruned fruit tree
branches.
</P>
<P>
They have produced 300,000 bags of mushrooms with the new
technique and processed them into 30,000 kg of dried mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
Most of China's mushrooms are produced in the southern sub-
tropical areas, but the new technique means that more northerly
regions may now produce mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
With its moderate weather conditions and drastic temperature
difference between day and night, the arid plateau north of the
Weihe River in central Shaanxi is an ideal place for growing
mushrooms, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
They estimate that the area can produce 80,000 tons of
mushrooms, valued at more than four billion yuan (some 482 million
US dollars), every year, using the new technique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Access to World Remote Island Nation Niue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Web has come to the remote
South Pacific atoll of Niue, with the setting up an Internet
access company on the island, the New Zealand Infotech Weekly
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Internet equipment was hooked up to Niue's frame-relay
telephone switch, which pipes data at 128 kilobit per second by
satellite between the island and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Other communications between Niue's 1,750 inhabitants and the
outside world are largely confined to the one aeroplane flight
each week to the "Rock of Polynesia," 2,400 kilometers north-east
of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
An engineer from Netlink, an Internet company in Wellington,
spent a week installing the equipment on the island earlier this
month, to give the island's 250 users free dial-in Web browsing
and e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Beefing up Position As Manufacturing Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- China's economic powerhouse
Shanghai has been placing great emphasis on developing local hi-
tech industry, as a key effort to maintain its position as the
leading manufacturing center.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several years, Shanghai has witnessed fast growth
in its burgeoning hi-tech industry, which include information
technology, bio-pharmaceuticals, and new materials. Latest
statistics show one-fifth of the nation's integrated circuit, one-
third of its telecommunications equipment, and 30 percent of IC
cards are produced by Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Such local pillar industries as automobiles, iron and steel,
equipment used for power station, fine chemicals, and household
apparatus also have occupied some 20 percent of the country's
markets each.
</P>
<P>
But the city has the need to boost its products up to world
standards and develop internationally-advanced technology and
products characteristic of creativity and advancement to cement
its position as the country's key manufacturing base, said Jiang
Yiren, vice-mayor of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has adopted favorable policies to lure overseas
investment to local large-scale projects and to encourage use of
scientific and technological achievements in production. Ten big
industrial and hi-tech projects are scheduled to become
operational within the year.
</P>
<P>
Some local group companies also have launched programs to train
personnel and increase recruitment of professionals.
</P>
<P>
Estimates say the hi-tech industry in Shanghai is expected to
yield 120 billion yuan (about 14.4 billion U.S. dollars) in output
value this year, up 25 percent on a yearly basis, or 18 percent of
local industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
This year Shanghai plans to use three billion dollars of
contractual overseas investment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
