<HEADLINE> Chinese Expedition Vessel Exits Arctic Circle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABOARD THE SNOW DRAGON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- After five days of
scientific research in the Chukchi Sea, the Chinese expedition
vessel "Snow Dragon" left the Arctic Circle early this morning, as
a result of unfavorable ice conditions.
</P>
<P>
The ship has returned to the Bering Sea, and the scientists on
board will investigate mainly into fishery resources there in the
coming two weeks, according to the adjusted plan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the team will wait for an improvement of the ice
conditions and continue its research in the Arctic Ocean, said
Chen Liqi, chief scientist of the expedition.
</P>
<P>
This is Chinese scientists' first expedition to the North Pole,
where they will study the effect of the North Pole on the global
climate, especially on that of China, the ecological system in
Arctic waters, and the atmosphere, geology, fishing, and marine
conditions of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
