<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's 1st Issue of Exchange Fund Notes to Be Listed in Mid-August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Hong Kong
(SEHK) and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) Monday signed a
listing agreement for the first issue of Exchange Fund Notes (EFNs)
on August 16 this year.
</P>
<P>
All 57 outstanding issues of Exchange Fund Notes, with a total
value of 34 billion HK dollars (about 4.36 billion U.S. dollars)
will be so listed, and trading in EFNs will be scripless,
according to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Yam, chief executive of the HKMA, said at the signing
ceremony that the listing will mark an important milestone in the
development of Hong Kong's debt market, and it will offer retail
investors an attractive and reliable investment opportunity.
</P>
<P>
Issued by the HKMA on behalf of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region Government for the account of the Exchange
Fund, the EFNs will be the inaugural issue to be listed on the
market.
</P>
<P>
All issues of Exchange Fund paper are fully backed by foreign
reserves. For every 780 HK dollars worth of Exchange Fund Notes,
there is 100 U.S. dollars held in the Exchange Fund.
</P>
<P>
"Investors therefore need have no concerns about the ability of
the Exchange Fund to repay this debt," Yam noted.
</P>
<P>
Lee Hon Chiu, chairman of the SEHK, said exchange trading of
debt securities would increase the transparency of corporate
borrowing, and it will also increase the liquidity of debt
securities and provide an additional sources of funds for issuers.
</P>
<P>
"One of the SEHK's objectives is to develop into a full
services securities market. Trading in EFNs and other debt
securities will expand the SEHK's product range," Lee said, adding
"it will also help increase the full potential of the debt
securities market."
</P>
<P>
At the ceremony, the HKMA also singed an agreement with the
Hong Kong Security Clearing Co. Ltd. to admit Exchange Fund Notes
as eligible securities in the Central Clearing and Settlement
System.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
