<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Province Shuts Down Coal Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Liaoning
province, the country's old industrial heartland, has joined a
nationwide bid to overhaul its coal-mining industry by shutting
down illegal or badly planned coal mines.
</P>
<P>
A total of 577 such mines have been closed down during the
first six months this year, involving coal output of 5.182 million
tons.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government originally had plans to close 440
mines involving coal output of 7.2 million tons this year.
</P>
<P>
Rampant and badly planned development of small coal mines have
been blamed for heavy pollution, waste of natural resources, and
over-production and low quality of coal in the province, China's
old industrial base.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning started to restructure the coal-mining industry in
1997, shutting down small mines without operation permits and
mines without proper pollution-reduction measures. The province
also put a brake on opening new coal mines when shutting down old
and small ones.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the province first organized a thorough
investigation to locate such illegal mines, and local governments
at all levels also formed special taskforce to carry out the work.
</P>
<P>
According to provincial officials, Liaoning will focus its work
during the later half year on inspection of the shut-down work to
ensure a permanent closing of such mines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
