<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Ex-Militiamen to Get Light Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Information Minister
Anwar Khalil has said he expected the majority of former members
of the pro-Israeli South Lebanon Army (SLA) to receive light
prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
"Most of them were low ranking and were not important. I
expect them to receive light sentences," Khalil was quoted Monday
by the Daily Star as saying.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the sentences would consist of fines or imprisonment,
the minister said "certainly they will be sent to prison, most of
them will remain there for one to three months only."
</P>
<P>
Khalil was speaking during a tour of Jezzine, a southern
Christian town which was vacated by the militia early in June
after a 14-year-old control.
</P>
<P>
The militia conducted the withdrawal under the pressure of
Lebanese Muslim Shiite group Hezbollah's military attacks in the
area which have claimed more than 150 SLA lives over the past
years.
</P>
<P>
After the SLA retreated into the Israeli occupied border zone
in south Lebanon, over 200 militiamen or ex-members decided to
hand themselves in to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
The trial of them are due to begin on Wednesday in the
military court.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south
Lebanon in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting its north
from Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
The 2,500-strong militia was established and funded by Israel
to help it patrol the border zone.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been
spearheading a guerrilla war trying to oust Israeli forces and
its proxy SLA out of the country.
</P>
<P>
In Lebanon, those collaborating with Israel are considered as
traitors as the country is officially at war with the Jewish
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
