<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Sightfirst China Act" Benefits Cataract Sufferers in Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- No one can imagine how excited
Rinzin Zhoima, who had suffered from cataracts since she was born,
felt when she saw her mother's face for the first time and how
blue the sky of her hometown was after she regained her eyesight
thanks to an operation.
</P>
<P>
Zhoima, aged 12, insisted on presenting a hada (a white silk
scarf presented as a gift by Tibetans) to Wang Dan, the doctor who
performed the operation this month.
</P>
<P>
"At last, I can see everything, and I can go to school in
September," she told reporters excitedly.
</P>
<P>
Zhoima, a native of Lhozhag County in southwest China's Tibet
Autonomous Region, is only one of 353 cataract sufferers in Tibet
who have regained their eyesight thanks to the "Sightfirst China
Act" this year.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the project, which was jointly launched by China's
Ministry of Health, the China Disabled Persons' Federation (CDPF)
and Lions Clubs International, a global non-governmental charity
organization, in 1997, is to provide free operations for cataract
sufferers in China.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of cataracts in Tibet is double that of inland
areas in China, due to the region's high elevation and strong
ultraviolet rays. Many cataract sufferers in Tibet can not receive
timely treatment because of economic, medical or communications
factors.
</P>
<P>
Last August, a group of doctors was sent to Lhasa, Shannan,
Qamdo and Nyingchi to conduct operations for cataract patients; as
a result, 1,129 people regained their sight.
</P>
<P>
Wang's team was the second batch to be sent to Tibet within two
years.
</P>
<P>
Since the project commenced in 1997, 92 medical teams have been
dispatched to 761 poor and remote counties in China, according to
Lu Manhua, vice-chairman of the rehabilitation division of the
CDPF.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that there are four million cataract patients in
the country at the moment, and the number is growing by 400,000
annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
