<HEADLINE> City Moves Old Trees to Keep Them Alive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A total of 34 trees each several
hundred years old in Taicang, east China's Jiangsu Province, have
been moved to a new place because of the reconstruction of the old
downtown area of the city.
</P>
<P>
To protect the old trees, the local government moved them to a
garden called Nanyuan. All the trees are thriving in their new
home.
</P>
<P>
Taicang was once famous for its great number of private gardens,
which had many old trees. As the old city area is now under
reconstruction, the city government is trying to preserve the
trees by moving them to new places.
</P>
<P>
The 34 trees moved to Nanyuan include some Chinese littleleaf
boxes over 600 years old.
</P>
<P>
The city government has earmarked 200,000 yuan for the
operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
