<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyans to Lose 17 Years in Life Expectancy Due to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations predicts a
17-year loss in life expectancy for Kenyans by the year 2010 as a
result of the spread of AIDS, the East African daily reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
AIDS, often referred to as a "poor man's disease", had 95
percent of all the infected persons living in developing countries
and a prevalence of 10 percent or more, according to the United
Nations 1999 Human Development Report.
</P>
<P>
The report said that due to the epidemic, life expectancy in
developing countries is expected to go down to 47 years by the
year 2010, back to what it was in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
"Although the disease is also spreading fast to areas
previously thought to be free of the virus like China and Russia,
the disease is still associated with poverty and especially the
marginalized people," the report warned.
</P>
<P>
Kenya which was placed 134th in last year's ranking dropped to
136 this year, due to an increase in the number of HIV/AIDS
cases, said Macleod Nyirongo, deputy regional representative of
the United Nations Development Program.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kenyan Health Minister Jackson Kalweo has decried
under- reporting of AIDS cases, saying that by the end of 1998,
only 750,000 of AIDS cases were reported with another 1.9 million
people estimated to be infected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Agronomist Sets Record for Dry-Field Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 19 (Xinhua) -- An agronomist in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province has set a record by raising the per ha yield of
wheat growing in dry fields from 750 kg to 6,000 kg.
</P>
<P>
Li Like, 64, quit his job as deputy head of the Shaanxi
Provincial Academy of Agricultural Sciences in 1981 in order to
grow high-yield wheat on arid land.
</P>
<P>
He finally succeeded after 18 years of experimentation.
</P>
<P>
As the first step, Li experimented with increasing the
application of phosphate fertilizer while turning up the soil and
regulating the use of water in the course of crop growth. The
method was spread to over 20 counties, increasing the annual wheat
output there by 400 million kg -- the per ha yield rising from 653
kg to 3,750 kg.
</P>
<P>
Later, Li found that rapid seepage of surface water prevents
higher yields. So, he left a higher wheat stock in the fields
during harvest time and put layers of straw in the fields in a bid
to preserve the moisture of the earth's surface. In this way, the
per ha yield rose to 6,000 kg.
</P>
<P>
North China has 20 million ha of arid land, and dry fields in
Shaanxi make up 60 percent of its total farmland. On average, the
per ha output of dry fields north of the Weihe River lingered
around 653 kg for many years. So Li's research is of vital
importance for dry field crop production in both Shaanxi and north
China as a whole.
</P>
<P>
An official from the Food and Agriculture Organization of the
United Nations (FAO) said Li's achievement has great significance
for dry field farming worldwide after a recent investigation in
Shaanxi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke071920 -Philippines Plans to Become Prime Tourism Destination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines positions itself to
become the prime Asian tourism destination in the coming years as
it landed the number 12 among the top Asia Pacific destinations
recently, a top official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gemma Cruz Araneta, secretary of the Department of Tourism
(DOT) said with the growth rate of 2.85 percent or 910,229 visitor
arrivals for the first five months of this year, the country is
well on its way to become the premier destination in Asia by the
year 2007.
</P>
<P>
"The DOT projects that travel and tourism contribution of 8.7
percent to gross national product to grow to 10.9 percent in 2007
and that 1.4 million jobs will be generated in the same year,"
Araneta told a meeting.
</P>
<P>
The tourism sector has been recognized by the Philippine
government as a golden opportunity and the DOT has tapped the
participation of Overseas Filipino Workers under the Tourism
Frontliners Program.
</P>
<P>
She added that the program presents a balanced development of
domestic and foreign markets and focuses equally on resort,
cultural and heritage tourism.
</P>
<P>
In order to tap into the 2.7-billion-U.S.-dollar international
tourism industry, the DOT has been participating in various
international trade fairs so as to encourage foreigners to visit
the Philippines, Araneta said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
