<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebei Fights Deterioration of Water Control Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The water control authorities
in north China's Hebei province have dealt with a series of cases
in which highway builders destroyed water control facilities.
</P>
<P>
The construction units responsible have been ordered to take
immediate remedial measures, including clearing away materials
blocking water courses and channels, to prepare for the flood
season.
</P>
<P>
Water control experts said flooding occurs frequently in Hebei,
and the destruction of water control facilities in recent years
will make the province even more vulnerable to floods.
</P>
<P>
Local media have given extensive coverage to illegal activities
by highway builders, such as dumping garbage into reservoirs and
rivers and building highways over reservoirs. As a result, the
provincial government formed a field survey team to conduct field
investigations and discovered that most highway contractors
ignored the requirement to map out relevant plans to prevent water
and soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the provincial government has issued two urgent
circulars calling for a halt to such destructive activities, and
more concern from highway builders for environmental protection
and the prevention of water and soil erosion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0207 </DOCNO>
