<HEADLINE> Sydney Ready to Deal With Traffic Curbs During 2000 Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Olympic Coordination Authority head
David Richmond said on Monday that Sydney will be able to cope
with restrictions on private vehicle use during the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that in the Olympic period, several major roads in
the central business district will be closed and footpaths will be
widened to cope with the 1.5 million visitors expected.
</P>
<P>
Richmond said that there would be some problems for business
but that had to be balanced against the unprecedented number of
visitors and their spending power.
</P>
<P>
Some restaurants have already planned to close during the Games
as they may be unable to provide fresh produce.
</P>
<P>
More flexible work hours have been encouraged in other
businesses to lessen the jams on the roads. 
