<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Defaults on Foreign Repayments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has defaulted on the
repayment of 4.6 billion shillings (62.1 million U.S. dollars)
owed to bilateral creditors, exposing its struggling economy to
further inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
The failure to meet external debt obligations, which was due by
the end of June, means that new lines of credit will be hard to
open and importers run the risk of incurring higher cost as a
result of dishonoring letter of credit, the East African weekly
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts say Kenyan importers might also be required
to pay cash up front for goods which would render pressure on the
battered Kenyan shilling as importers and investors seeking to
repatriate their profits and principal investment scramble for the
available hard currency.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper said, the Kenyan government is said to be
honoring its obligation to the International Monetary Fund and
the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The debt in question owed mainly to France, Japan, Austria and
Britain include 3.5 billion shillings of principal repayments and
1.1 billion shillings of interest payments.
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that the amount of debt Kenya can't pay is
expected to rise following a sharp increase in Kenya's external
repayment obligations from 23.6 billion shillings in 1998/99 to
33.5 billion shillings in 1999/ 2000 fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
