<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violent Crime Rates Decline in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Violent crime rates in the
United States last year declined 7 percent to their lowest levels
since the Justice Department began tracking the figure in 1973,
Attorney General Janet Reno announced here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, crimes against property including burglary, car
theft and household theft also fell 12 percent to their lowest
levels since 1973, according to this year's National Crime
Victimization Survey released Sunday.
</P>
<P>
From 1993 to 1998, violent crime rates fell 27 percent, from 50
to 37 per 1,000 people aged 12 or older, the survey said. Violent
crime includes rape or sexual assault, robbery, aggravated assault
and simple assault.
</P>
<P>
The report said preliminary figures released separately by the
Federal Bureau of Investigation have shown that the number of
murders dropped about 8 percent between 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno said there is no one reason for the
drop of violent crime rates. She gave the Clinton administration's
policies credit for combining the effects of several strategies.
</P>
<P>
"It's because of more police officers on the streets, tougher
sentences, more prosecutions, better prevention programs, a
healthy economy and a new approach to crime fighting that involves
a closer working relationship between communities and federal,
state and local law enforcement," Reno said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
