<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kennedy Jr. Likely Dead, Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 19 (Xinhua) -- John F. Kennedy Jr., his wife
and her sister were probably dead in a plane crash on Friday night,
according to a Coast Guard official Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to shift, and I say shift very purposely, from
our focus on search and rescue to search and recovery," said Rear
Adm. Richard M. Larrabee at a press conference broadcast live on
tv in Aquinnah, Massachusetts Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the search had no major progress on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 38-year-old Kennedy was piloting his single-engine plane,
with his wife, Carolyn Bessette Kennedy, 33, and her older sister
Lauren Bessette on board, when it crashed in the waters off Martha
's Vineyard on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
His father, President John F. Kennedy, was assassinated in
1963 in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
The searchers zeroed in on a spot at the bottom of the sea
after picking up an automatic emergency signal Sunday, while
Americans grieved over the almost certain deaths of Kennedy, his
wife and her sister.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday in Washington, President Bill Clinton offered the
prayers of a nation, saying the Kennedys "have suffered much and
given more" as a family over the past 40 years.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people, including Coast Guardsmen and members of
the Air Force and National Guard, concentrated on a 1,000-square-
kilometer area off Gay Head, on the southwestern edge of Martha's
Vineyard, using ships, helicopters, planes and all-terrain
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, searchers found little more than the fragment
of a headrest and some insulation. Saturday's search had yielded a
wheel, a headrest, part of a plane support, a prescription bottle
belonging to Kennedy's wife and a piece of baggage belonging to
his sister-in-law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
