<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Reports High Foreign Trade Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 19 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province,
one of the country's major exporting regions, generated 7.9
billion U.S. dollars-worth of foreign trade in the first half of
this year, up 15.7 percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The province exported 5.439 billion U.S. dollars-worth of goods,
an increase of 10.5 percent, and imported 2.46 billion U.S.
dollars-worth of commodities, up 28.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The private sector is playing a bigger role in foreign trade,
with its exports hitting 46 million U.S. dollars-worth and imports
topping 8.3 million U.S. dollars-worth during the period.
</P>
<P>
China as a whole saw a decline of 4.6 percent in exports in the
first half of the year, but there were some signs of recovery
later in the period, according to the latest Customs figures.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the General Administration of Customs
show that China's exports reached 83 billion U.S. dollars-worth
between January and June, while imports surged 16.6 percent to 75
billion U.S. dollars-worth, bringing the total trade volume to 158
billion U.S. dollars-worth, up 4.4 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
