<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Keep Deficit at 68.4 Billion Pesos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government planned
to improve its revenue performance in second half of 1999 while
keeping the deficit target for the whole year at 68.4 billion
pesos (1.71 billion U.S. dollars), the Department of Finance (DoF)
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In its first year accomplishment report, the DoF said that
financing economic growth is an enormous challenge for the fiscal
sector, particularly the remaining economic agenda on
liberalization and deregulation.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve this, the government is keen on
implementing the right mix of fiscal programs through the
implementation of effective tax administration, borrowing and
privatization activities.
</P>
<P>
"Tax reforms will be implemented to remove distortions in the
tax system, enhance its equity features, and promote the
protection of the environment," the DoF reported.
</P>
<P>
The report added that these tax reforms include rationalization
of fiscal incentives, taxation of the financial sector, and the
introduction of the "green" taxes.
</P>
<P>
The DoF also intended to introduce the taxation of electronic
commerce as the economy becomes more integrated with the
globalization of markets.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the government is expected to borrow
from bilateral and multilateral funds as these provide lower
interest rates and longer maturities.
</P>
<P>
The government opted to an expansionary fiscal stand to
stimulate the economy because it believes that pump-priming the
economy over the next two years will lead to attaining a balanced
budget in order to revert to fiscal surpluses in the medium-term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
