<HEADLINE> British Mission Visits Sri Lanka to Boost Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A British Trade delegation is due
to begin a five-day visit to Sri Lanka from Monday to accelerate
trade between the two countries, trade officials said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Internal and International Commerce and Food T.
Wickramaratne is scheduled to discuss business prospects with the
delegation as well as facilitate one-to-one business contacts
through his ministry, a ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the British delegation's visit is to establish
one-to-one contacts with the Sri Lankan business community, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Leicestershire Chamber of Commerce and Industry has led six
successful trade missions to Sri Lanka in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
The delegation represents a variety of business interests
ranging from equipment and machinery for the garment industry,
fabrics and garment accessories, pharmaceuticals, military and
aerospace equipment.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's trade with Britain has grown by 51 percent to
53,535 million rupees (811 million U.S. dollars) in 1998 over 1996
and the balance of trade in Sri Lanka's favor has increased to
13,941 million rupees (211 million dollars) from 7,299 million
rupees (122 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Garments which is the main export from Sri Lanka to Britain has
increased largely in recent years. Other exports include tea,
desiccated coconut, natural rubber, coconut fibre, soft toys,
wooden articles and tobacco. Britain exports to Sri Lanka are
mainly machinery and mechanical appliances.
</P>
<P>
Britain is one of Sri Lanka's top 10 investors in areas such as
textiles, garments and accessories, electronic products, security
printing, tourism and infrastructure development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
