<HEADLINE> Private Businesses Contribute to Zhejiang's Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Private businesses have been
playing an increasingly important role in economic development in
east China's Zhejiang Province, contributing nearly half of the
GDP generated in the country's fourth-largest economic powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
Local self-employed households and private enterprises created
as much as 480 billion yuan-worth of industrial output value in
1998, accounting for 43 percent of the local total GDP.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang's Governor Chai Songyue has praised private businesses
for their contributions to local economic growth in increasing
employment and the local government's tax revenue, as well as the
growth of local urbanization.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses are expanding by means of trade markets
totaling some 4,400 in the province, where over 86 percent of the
total 750,000 operators are self-employed or from private
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The local booming of private businesses is regarded as a result
of the upgrading of the status of the private sector and the
adoption of a series of favorable policies for them by the
province in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Large-scale private enterprises are now mushrooming in Zhejiang,
with the number of private enterprises each with over 10 million
yuan of registered capital reaching 404 and the number of
enterprises each with 100 million yuan of output value reaching 36.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
