<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rafter Knocks U.S. out of Davis Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- After dropping each of the
first two sets, Patrick Rafter rallied to beat a weary Todd Martin
4-6, 5-7, 6-3, 6-2, 6-4 on Sunday and send Australia on to the
Davis Cup semifinal round.
</P>
<P>
Martin's loss knocks the United States out of the competition
and sets up a meeting between Australia and Russia, which earned
its spot in the semis when Marat Safin downed Karol Kucera of
Slovakia 2-6, 6-4, 6-2, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Rafter rallied from deficits of two sets and three games in the
fifth set to put out a victory at Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
Rafter broke Martin for the third straight service game to take
a 5-4 lead and saved out the match at love to clinch the best-of-
five quarterfinal with a 4-1 overall win.
</P>
<P>
After a neutral doctor declared him fit to play, Martin gave it
all he had against the world's second-ranked player. Even after
Rafter came back to force the fifth set, Martin got the early
break in the second game of the final set and opened a 3-0 lead.
But the American proceeded to drop his final three service games.
</P>
<P>
Teenager Lleyton Hewitt completed the 4-1 series win by beating
Alex O'Brien 7-5, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Belgium reached the Davis Cup semifinals for the first time in
the modern era when Xavier Malisse beat Switzerland's Roger
Federer in the first reverse singles match of the day.
</P>
<P>
Cedric Pioline beat Brazilian Gustavo Kuerten 6-3, 6-4, 6-4 to
send France to a semifinal meeting with Belgium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
