<HEADLINE> Hungarians Win Modern Pentathlon Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Hungary's Gabor Balogh took the
men's individual title in the 39th Modern Pentathlon World
Championships on Sunday, helping Hungary take the team title.
</P>
<P>
Balogh, 23, sixth in Mexico City last year, took the lead after
the second discipline, fencing. But his lead over Libor Capalini
of the Czech Republic was down to just eight points after four
events, which means he had only a two-second advantage in the last
discipline, running.
</P>
<P>
Few expected Balogh to be able to maintain the first position
for he was more than a minute slower than Capalini during the
qualification race on Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, Balogh eventually won the race 12 seconds ahead of his
closest rival.
</P>
<P>
By winning the world championship, Balogh qualified for 2000
Olympics in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The team gold medal went to Hungary, who was 430 points ahead
of Lithuania and another 124 points ahead of Blears.
</P>
<P>
Team order was established on the basis of the total individual
scores of the team members. 
</P>
