<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insect Pests Under Control in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, July 19 (Xinhua) -- A massive infestation of insects
in northeast China's Liaoning Province, which has affected about
200,000 ha of forests, has been basically brought under control.
</P>
<P>
Triggered by abnormally warm weather last winter, the
infestation involved more than 20 species of insects, and more
than five million trees were affected.
</P>
<P>
The province organized experts for joint diagnosis of the
infestation, and they worked out biological and chemical measures
to kill the pests. Local governments at all levels raised nearly
one million yuan (120,000 US dollars) for the work.
</P>
<P>
About 20 percent of the affected forests have received
treatment, and 356,000 diseased trees have been chopped down,
according to Sun Yongping, director of the province's forest
insect pest prevention office.
</P>
<P>
"The threat from the first generation of the pests is easing,
but another round of infestation by the second generation may
break out this autumn or next year," Sun said.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning is expected to set up an early-warning system
regarding insect infestation so as to deal with the problem as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has a forest coverage rate of only about 30 percent,
with 4.45 million ha of trees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
