again in the next elections," she was quoted by The Indonesian
Observer Monday as saying.
</P>
<P>
While saying it is too early to celebrate the triumph, Megawati
told the party to become a "humble victor".
</P>
<P>
The PDI-P gained about 34 percent of votes in the June 7
general elections, far outnumbering the ruling Golkar Party which
trails the leading party with around 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
The three-day leadership meeting is expected to reconfirm the
party's nomination of Megawati as its presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
"Her nomination was mandated by the party's previous congress,
so we hope everybody will stick to what was decided by the
congress," the party's Deputy Chairman Soetardjo Soerjogoeritno
said.
</P>
<P>
Soetardjo said the meeting would draw up the criteria for
candidates to fill seats in the House of Representatives won by
the party from its leftover votes, as stipulated by the General
Elections Commission (KPU).
</P>
<P>
He refused to confirm whether party leaders would discuss a
coalition arrangement with other parties, saying they would wait
until the KPU announced the official poll results. The
announcement is tentatively scheduled for July 25.
</P>
<P>
Attendants will also evaluate the party's performance across
the country, Soetardjo was quoted by The Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
