<HEADLINE> Heyns Shatters 200m Breaststroke Record Twice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- South African swimmer Penny
Heyns twice broke the five-year-old women's 200 meter breaststroke
world record at the Janet Evans Invitational in Los Angeles on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Heyns, world record holder in the 50 and 100-meter breaststroke,
set the record with two minutes 24.69 seconds in the preliminary,
bettering the mark of 2:24.76 set by Australian Rebecca Brown in
1994.
</P>
<P>
She then eclipsed the new record to 2:24.51 in the finals.
</P>
<P>
Heyns, competing in the sixth annual Janet Evan Invitational
competition, had completed Olympic double-gold in the 100 and 200
meter breaststroke in the 1996 Atlanta Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Tom Wilkens, a member of the 1998 U.S. World Championships team,
claimed victory in the 200-meter breaststroke in 2:16.09 and the
400-meter individual medley in 4:23.79.
</P>
<P>
Joanne Malar also won twice, taking the 200-meter freestyle in
2:02.22 and the 400-meter medley in 4:42.63.
</P>
<P>
South African Ryk Neethling won his third event of the meet,
taking the 200-meter free in 1:50.71.
</P>
<P>
Olympic gold medalist Jenny Thompson won her second event, the
50 meter freestyle, in a meet-record 25.75. Roland Schoeman won
the men's 50m in 22.93.
</P>
<P>
The meet, named for the American woman swimmer who set and
still holds records for 400, 800 and 1,500 freestyle a decade ago,
concludes Sunday. The four-day event has drawn over 700
competitors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
