<HEADLINE> Philippines' Bank Loans Inch up In May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- For the first time in months,
bank's lending of the Philippines inched up by 0.3 percent in May
from 1.3 percent contraction in April, Malaya newspaper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted central bank governor Rafael Buenaventura as
saying that commercial banks' total loan portfolio expanded by 3.6
billion pesos (90 million U.S. dollars) to 1.468 trillion pesos
(36.7 billion dollars) from the previous month's portfolio of
1.4652 trillion pesos (36.63 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Since loan portfolio expanded, the system's non-performing or
souring loans (NPL) lightly dropped from 14.48 percent in April to
14.45 percent in May, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
Buenaventura said that both the increase in outstanding loans
and the minimal decrease in NPLs are encouraging sighs of renewing
vitality in the banking system.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the asset deterioration of the Philippine
banking system is lower than NPL ratio of the other countries in
the region ranging from 19 to 75 percent as of May.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, banks continue to build up their loan loss reserves
way above the requirement of the central bank, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the governor, the loan loss reserves as of May
amounted to 70.8 billion pesos (1.77 billion dollars), covering
33.4 percent of soured loans and accounting for 4.8 percent of the
total loan portfolio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
