<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Needs 6 Billion Dollars to Plug Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia needed between 5.5 and 6
billion U.S. dollars in new foreign loans to plug the 1999/2000
state budget deficit, according to the National Development
Planning Board (Bappenas) Chairman Boediono.
</P>
<P>
He said part of the needed loans had been secured after the
country's largest donors, including Japan and the World Bank,
confirmed their financial support earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
"The total (overseas loans) we need is between 5.5 billion and
6 billion dollars for the 1999/2000 fiscal year (ending March
2000). But some (of the needed loan) have been pledged," he was
quoted by The Jakarta Post Monday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Boediono said the remaining budget shortfall was expected to be
covered by commitments from donors at the upcoming Consultative
Group on Indonesia (CGI) meeting in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia particularly needs program loans to help finance the
costly bank restructuring program, which required 17 trillion
rupiah (2.54 billion dollars) of the current state budget.
</P>
<P>
The government, the World Bank and the chairman of the CGI have
been pressured by Indonesian opposition parties and several
non-governmental organizations to postpone the upcoming donors
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties say new loan negotiations should be held
under the country's next administration, which will be formed
later this year.
</P>
<P>
However, Boediono said a delay of the CGI meeting would damage
confidence in the economy because the market would be nervous
about the hole in the state budget.
</P>
<P>
He also said the current administration would only negotiate
for loans to finance the 1999/2000 state budget.
</P>
<P>
The government would not negotiate for loans needed for the
2000/2001 state budget, he said, adding this would be the
responsibility of the next administration.
</P>
<P>
Several government officials earlier said several CGI members
were ready to provide some 5 billion dollars in new loans at the
next CGI meeting. The country received some 7.9 billion dollars
from CGI last year.
</P>
<P>
Coordinating Minister for Economy, Finance and Industry
Ginandjar Kartasasmita is scheduled to leave for Tokyo on Monday,
where he will meet with high-ranking Japanese officials and seek
Japan's support at the CGI meeting.
</P>
<P>
Japan is Indonesia's largest donor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
