<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Medicine Storage for Emergencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- China plans to establish a multi-
level medicine storage and supply network in order to provide
efficient medical aids in the wake of natural disasters, epidemics
and other emergencies.
</P>
<P>
The network will include central and local medicine storage
facilities storing some 1.2 billion yuan (145 million U.S. dollars)
worth of drugs and medical appliances, said today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The country has decided to allocate 550 million yuan (66.3
million dollars) to prepare medical supplies for possible
nationwide disasters, while local medicine storage facilities will
be established with funds from provincial governments.
</P>
<P>
China established a medicine storage system composed of 13
medicine storage banks in the 1970s, all funded and managed by the
central government.
</P>
<P>
"However, the country's shift to a market-oriented economy has
put some storage banks into budget difficulties since the 1990s,
leading to a shrinking medical storage that no longer satisfies
the State's need in times of emergencies," the report said.
</P>
<P>
Pharmaceutical Department under the State Economic and Trade
Commission will be responsible for the overall management and
supervision of the network.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Population Cooperation Expanding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Population Institute
intends to expand cooperation with China in the next few years to
increase world understanding of China's family planning program,
today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quotes a senior official
with the institute as saying in Beijing that the cooperation will
also introduce China's experience in managing its economy and its
social welfare system to other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The institute plans to cooperate with the State Family Planning
Commission (SFPC) to publish a Chinese edition of its volume on
success stories in population development.
</P>
<P>
The two bodies will also discuss further personnel exchanges so
that more Chinese family planning workers can be trained in
delivering information and services and have the chance to observe
population programs in the United States, said Werner Fornos,
president of the institute.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Population Institute, launched in 1969, is the largest
U.S. non-governmental organization in the population field. It has
maintained a close co-operative relationship with the SFPC since
1984.
</P>
<P>
Fornos said he has witnessed great changes in China including a
sharp decline in population growth, improved economic conditions,
success in poverty eradication efforts, empowering of women,
community projects, and improvements in sanitation, housing and
education.
</P>
<P>
"Looking into the year 2000 and beyond, I think China is a
valuable partner in international development, especially in south-
to-south relations and teaching countries in the developing world
to manage their economy and social system," he said.
</P>
<P>
He highly commended China's Family Planning University in
Nanjing, the only one in the world, the paper reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
