<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0050 GMT July 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS -- Ethnic clashes between the Hausa and Yoruba
communities erupted on Sunday in the southern town of Shagamu,
about 30 kilometers north of Lagos, killing at least 10 people.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian riot police have moved in to take control of the
serious violence but the situation in the town is still tense with
armed groups roaming the streets, one witness was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The clashes occurred after a Hausa woman was killed outside her
home late last week and then Hausas came out in large numbers on
Saturday night. (Nigeria-Ethnic Clashes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Ireland's Prime Minister Bertie Ahern warned on
Sunday that the deadline for decommissioning all IRA weapons by
May 2000 might not be met because of the recent setbacks in the
Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
But he insisted there is still "plenty to build on" in efforts
to put the Good Friday Agreement back on course.
</P>
<P>
Ahern, due to meet British Prime Minister Tony Blair in London
on Tuesday to assess the state of the peace process and plan a
review, said: "We have to get to the endgame on this eventually."
(UK-Republican-Arms Handover)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Visiting Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said
on Sunday that Israel will strive for peace with its neighbors so
as to strengthen the country. He left open the option of a
Palestinian state but refused to budge on the thorny issue of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Barak, in a taped interview broadcast by NBC, said that time is
now right to "leave no stone unturned" in the road to strengthen
Israel "through peace with all its neighbors". (US-Israel-Barak)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. warplanes on Sunday struck Iraqi missile and
communication sites in the southern no-fly zone, the U.S. military
said.
</P>
<P>
Targets included a surface-to-air missile site near Abu, about
200 miles (320 km) south of Baghdad, and a communication site near
Al Khidr, about 150 miles (240km) southeast of Baghdad, said the U.
S. Central Command, based at Mac Dill Air Force Base in Tampa,
Florida. (US-Iraq-Airstrikes) 
</P>
