<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Trade Issues Play Central Part in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 19 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard Sunday wound up his two-week visit to Japan and the United
States, which was seen by analysts as a trip to boost Australian
exports and discuss disturbing trade issues.
</P>
<P>
With its recent economic boom and ability to ride out the
Asian financial storm, Australia feels the need to expand its
overseas markets, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Australia's gross domestic product grew 5 percent in 1998,
faster than the U.S. economy and more than double the aggregate
growth rate of the Organization for Economic Co-operation and
Development (OECD).
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund and OECD forecast that in 2000
Australia will grow faster than all Group-7 economies.
</P>
<P>
But on the other hand, Australia, as an agricultural exporter
with a tiny domestic market, has no choice but to persist with its
arguments for free trade, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the markets of Japan and the United States, the
top two trade partners of Australia, are of much significance to
the country's exports, they said.
</P>
<P>
On trade, Howard's trip to Japan has two aims. The first aim is
to broaden Australia's exports to Japan from traditional
commodities to new industries, they said.
</P>
<P>
On the first day of the five-day visit to Japan, Howard and
his Japanese counterpart Keizo Obuchi reached agreement on a joint
approach to electric commerce and a millennium conference to
discuss new technology.
</P>
<P>
Japan also approved the Commonwealth Bank of Australia to
register to trade securities in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
The e-commerce agreement will see the removal of legal
obstacles to electronic transactions and the promotion of
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
The Second aim is to push for more opening of Japanese
agricultural markets, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Howard used his meeting with Obuchi to urge Japan to be
committed to reforming its own economy, opening its markets and
promoting free trade.
</P>
<P>
But the Japanese, who have yet to get rid of the effect of
Asian financial crisis and pursue the policy of food security,
greater agricultural self-sufficiency, offered only their own
version on the issues.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Obuchi explained our basic position on
agriculture, which is going to be the agenda of WTO negotiations,"
said Japanese Foreign Ministry spokesman Chikahito Harada.
</P>
<P>
Howard's U.S. trip was overshadowed even before it started,
following President Bill Clinton's announcement of imposing a
quota on lamb import from Australia, New Zealand and some other
countries, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The United States also slapped a 9 percent tariff on sales
within the quota and a 40 percent penalty on sales outside the
quota.
</P>
<P>
Analysts of the Australian lamb industry said the decision
could cost the country up to 9.9 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although Howard condemned the decision as "appalling" and
"hypocritical", he acknowledged that he had little chance of
having the decision reversed.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is constantly encouraging people to support
free trade and condemning others who don't practice it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But when it suits their own convenience, because they are the
strongest country in the world, they just slam on these punitive
tariffs."
</P>
<P>
"In the end, we can only complain - and protect our own," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Lamb dominated the meeting between Howard and Clinton in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
And Howard warned Clinton that his attack on Australian lamb
producers had harmed bilateral relations more than any decision in
recent memory.
</P>
<P>
"I made it plain to him the issue had caused a greater adverse
reaction in Australia on a trade matter than any other trade issue
that I could remember," Howard said.
</P>
<P>
"The president understood we were very angered about it and
very upset about it," he added.
</P>
<P>
From the U.S. political perspective, the decision was obvious,
the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. consumers are spread throughout the United States and
will not change their votes on inferior and slightly more
expensive lamb as a result of the decision.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. farmers, however, have made it very clear to their
congressional representatives that they would change their votes
and the representatives have pressured the White House.
</P>
<P>
There are votes and political benefits in caving in to
protectionism, the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
In this scenario, Howard still has a great deal of difficult
talks ahead to promote Australia's exports, even after he
concluded his trade mission to the two countries, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese in Cairo Slam Lee Teng-hui's Separatist Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Chinese community in
Cairo, Egypt, on Sunday slammed the recent separatist remarks made
by Taiwan's Lee Teng-hui that the cross-Straits relationship is "
state-to-state."
</P>
<P>
Liu Huaiyu, a doctor, said at a meeting organized by the
Chinese Embassy here that Lee Teng-hui's fallacy has exposed his
premeditated intentions to divide China and split the Chinese
nation.
</P>
<P>
If Lee's attempts should succeed, China would be dismembered
and face the danger of war, and ethnic Chinese all over the world
would lose dignity, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed indignation over Lee's separatist remarks, adding
that they can not represent the wishes of the Taiwanese people.
</P>
<P>
Lee Teng-hui, leader of the Taiwan authorities, claimed in an
interview with a German radio early this month that the Taiwan
authorities had defined the relationship across the Taiwan Straits
as "state-to-state, or at least special state-to-state relations."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has condemned Lee's remarks as an utter
exposure of his premeditated intentions to divide Chinese
territory and sovereignty, and create "two Chinas," "one China,
one Taiwan" or "Taiwan's independence."
</P>
<P>
Ge Xin'ai, a former women's table tennis world champion and a
coach in Egypt now, said it is universally acknowledged that there
is only one China in the world and that Taiwan is an inseparable
part of China.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Chinese living abroad are firmly opposed to Lee's
separatist remarks and hope that China will be reunified as soon
as possible, she said.
</P>
<P>
All other participants in the meeting also lashed out at Lee's
separatist remarks and expressed confidence that his attempts to
split the country are doomed to failure and that China will
eventually accomplish its sacred task of national reunification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990719.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiangsu State Sector Profitable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 19 (Xinhua) -- The state sector in east China's
Jiangsu Province, one of the country's economic powerhouses, has
become profitable this year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the state-owned enterprises and major non-
public manufacturers in the province generated a total of 102.1
billion yuan in added industrial value in the first half of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned enterprises achieved 1.1 billion yuan in
profits during the January-May period, compared with a loss of 839
million yuan during the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts attribute the upward trend to years of
restructuring and improved management.
</P>
<P>
They predict that the momentum will continue throughout the
year.
</P>
<P>
Jiangsu achieved 155.4 billion yuan in gross domestic product (
GDP) in the first quarter of the year, accounting for one-tenth of
the country's total GDP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
