<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Move Downtown Manufacturers to Suburbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 19 (Xinhua) -- This, China's leading industrial
and commercial city has decided not to start any new industrial
projects in its downtown districts in principle.
</P>
<P>
An official with the municipal economic commission noted that
the decision is part of a massive program to remove local
industries to the outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the city has started to build nine
city-level manufacturing centers with a total designed area of 250
sq km on its outskirts.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the new centers have so far registered
about 2,000 industrial projects, of which 764 are funded by
overseas investors, including 46 funded by some of the world's top
500 multinationals.
</P>
<P>
These new centers have been busily building up their major
industries in line with the city's industrial restructuring plan.
The Jiading Industrial Zone, for example, has already established
four pillar industries: automotive accessories, refrigeration
equipment, electronic goods and metal processing.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts predict that the industrial centers will become
modernized satellite towns in the years to come.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
