<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Warplanes Strike Iraqi Sites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- U.S. warplanes on Sunday
struck Iraqi missile and communication sites in the southern
no-fly zone, the U.S. military said.
</P>
<P>
Targets included a surface-to-air missile site near Abu, about
200 miles (320 km) south of Baghdad, and a communication site near
Al Khidr, about 150 miles (240km) southeast of Baghdad, said the
U.S. Central Command, based at Mac Dill Air Force Base in Tampa,
Florida.
</P>
<P>
The command said the strike was carried by U.S. Air Force
F-16s, along with a Navy F-a-18 and F-14 aircraft, which fired
precision guided missiles at their targets at about 10:15 a.m.
EST (1415 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Iraq said 14 people were killed and 17 injured by the U.S.
strikes.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones in the southern and northern Iraq were
imposed by the United States and Britain right after the Gulf
War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has announced that any foreign warplanes invading its
space would violate its sovereignty and would be fired.  
</P>
</TEXT>
