<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Strive for Peace with Its Neighbors: Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak said on Sunday that Israel will strive for peace with
its neighbors so as to strengthen the country. He left open the
option of a Palestinian state but refused to budge on the thorny
issue of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Barak, in a taped interview broadcast by NBC, said that time is
now right to "leave no stone unturned" in the road to strengthen
Israel "through peace with all its neighbors".
</P>
<P>
"I believe that within 15 months from now, we will know whether
we have a major breakthrough on the Palestinian, Syrian, and
Lebanese tracks or not," he told Jim Russert, the anchor man of
NBC television's "Meet the Press" program.
</P>
<P>
"This is a moment of truth. We should live up to the challenge
and put an end to the conflict of 100 years while strengthening,
rather than weakening, the state of Israel," he added.
</P>
<P>
When ask about the possibility of a "true" Palestinian state to
be set up in the future, Barak said, "when the time comes, the
Palestinians will have to negotiate with us what kind of entity is
shaped for them in a context, a wider context of all the other
issues that are on the table."
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Barak, who arrived here on Wednesday for his first
visit to the United States since winning Israel's general election
last May, remained firm on the issue of Jerusalem, which both the
Israelis and the Palestinians have claimed to be the center of
their states.
</P>
<P>
"A united sovereign Jerusalem is our capital, and will remain
so forever," Barak said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he is willing to make compromises to
achieve peace with Syria, but it depends on what the Syrians will
offer on such matters as stopping Lebanese terror, water
resources, the opening of embassies and borders, security and
early warning arrangements and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In contrast with late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin's
view, Barak ruled out the need for the presence of U.S. troops in
the Golan Heights, which Israel seized from Syria in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think that U.S. troops will be needed in the Golan
Heights. Maybe there will be a need for a few dozens of foreign
observers or controllers or members of inspections teams. All like
this would be provided by either American or other U.N. leading
members," he said.
</P>
<P>
Barak also tried to exclude the involvement of the CIA in the
Mid-east peace process. "Once we resume trust with our neighbors,
I don't think that there will be a real need for CIA agents to
look after the last Palestinian policemen," he said.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who has held several rounds of talks with President Bill
Clinton in the past few days, implied in his remarks that the
United States should be "sensitive to the needs of the Arabs"
while remaining Israel's "best ally.".
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. has been and will be in the future an ally of Israel,
may be the best ally we have. At the same time, without being an
honest broker sensitive to the needs of the Arabs, it cannot
facilitate the kind of services for the peace process," said
Barak, who is to have further meetings with Clinton on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
